# Cyrius Field Notes — Compiler & Toolchain Evolution
# Retrospectives, regressions, and patterns from the cc2→cc3→cc4 arc.
# Compiler internals, build system conventions, and toolchain lessons.

[[entries]]
name = "when_cyrius_gets_serious_about_math"
description = "Performance projection: what happens when cc2 gets real optimizations"
category = "cyrius"
---
Current benchmarks (v0.11.0, cc2 2.4.0 — no optimizer):

  fixed_mul:       410ns
  sin_lookup:      414ns
  pcache_hit:      462ns
  render_frame:    2.2ms
  +sprites:        2.9ms
  tick budget:     28.6ms (35Hz)

cc2 today: single-pass, no constant folding, no inlining, no register
allocation. Every function call spills to stack. Every intermediate
value goes through rax/rcx ping-pong. And it still renders DOOM at
2.9ms per frame with 90% headroom.

What happens when cc2 gets:
  - Constant folding: fx_from_int(320) → immediate 20971520
  - Inlining: asr() disappears into the caller
  - Register allocation: hot variables stay in r12-r15
  - Dead store elimination: unused computations vanish

Conservative estimate:
  fixed_mul:     410ns → ~50ns  (8x, register-to-register multiply)
  render_frame:  2.2ms → ~0.3ms (7x, inlined inner loops)
  +sprites:      2.9ms → ~0.4ms

Sub-millisecond DOOM frames. 2,500 FPS potential. In 107KB.
From a 29KB seed.

At that point the renderer isn't the bottleneck for anything.
Not DOOM. Not kiran. Not a real-time physics sim.
The math is just... free.

     GAME OVER

    CONTINUE?  ▓

  9... 8... 7...

     INSERT 29KB

[[entries]]
name = "the_road_to_three"
description = "v3.0 retrospective: what it took to ship a sovereign compiler at 3.0"
category = "cyrius"
---
THE ROAD TO 3.0: A RETROSPECTIVE

From v2.0 to v3.0 in one session. Here is what happened:

BUGS KILLED: 18 bugs (#14-#31). The worst:
  - #14: SIGSEGV on 6000+ lines (heap collision between &&/|| and continue patches)
  - #16: var buf[N] shared across functions (FINDVAR forward scan → last-match)
  - #30: 8KB string data buffer silent overflow (garbled test output)
  - #31: PRLINE(S) never existed (call to address 0 → SIGSEGV)

FEATURES SHIPPED:
  - Multi-width types, sizeof, unions, bitfields
  - ELF .o relocatable output
  - cyrius-x bytecode VM with recursion
  - 33 stdlib modules (up from 28)
  - base64, chrono, flock, hashmap_fast parity
  - cyrius build tool with test/fuzz/soak/watch/deps
  - P(-1) scaffold hardening process

PATTERNS THAT WORKED:
  1. Test after EVERY change. Not after the feature is done.
  2. Two-step bootstrap for any heap offset change.
  3. P(-1) before new work — find what is broken before building on it.
  4. Pin downstream CI to RELEASED versions, not dev.
  5. var buf[N] is BYTES not ELEMENTS — document, warn, check.

PATTERNS THAT DIDN'T:
  1. Tail call optimization — too fragile with >6 args and nested calls.
     Disabled for cx, guarded for x86. Correctness over performance.
  2. SIMD hashmap (hashmap_fast) — slower than scalar for small maps.
     Kept for API parity but not the default recommendation.
  3. Auto-discover sibling repos in soak test — too many false positives.
     Hardcoded validated repo list instead.

THE NUMBERS:
  29KB seed → 231KB compiler
  33 stdlib modules, 200+ functions
  27 test suites, 345 assertions
  8 downstream repos, 964+ combined assertions
  0 open bugs
  186 vidya entries
  1 language. 1 toolchain. No dependencies.

Assembly up.

[[entries]]
name = "r12_loop_var_regression_lesson"
description = "v3.3.5–3.3.12: the loop-var-in-r12 opt that doubled render_frame time — perf test, don't assume"
category = "cyrius"
---
CONTEXT: v3.3.5 added a "loop variable register cache" — r12 reserved as the
loop counter register. At `while(...)`, if the condition started with a local
var, cc3 cached it in r12. Loads became `mov rax, r12` (3 bytes) instead of
`mov rax, [rbp-N]` (7 bytes). Stores wrote both r12 and stack for call safety.

The CORRECTNESS tests all passed. 30/30 .tcyr files green. Self-hosting
byte-identical. No regression in the cyrius audit.

Then cyrius-doom's benchmarks caught it:
  render_frame:  2.2ms → 4.3ms   (2x slower)
  fixed_mul:     435ns → 662ns   (1.5x slower)

The cost of `push r12 / pop r12` on every function call vastly exceeded the
savings from caching one loop counter. Every call paid 2 extra instructions
of overhead. The win was small; the tax was on every caller.

WORSE: the frame shift also broke 7+ arg functions (stack offset moved from
[rbp+16] to [rbp+24]). That was Bug #32 in v3.3.11, filed separately before
anyone connected it to r12.

v3.3.12 REVERTED the r12 cache entirely. Prologue back to `push rbp; mov rbp,
rsp`. Frame stayed at +16 again. The dead GLVR/SLVR accessors sat in util.cyr
until v3.4.16 when they were finally cleaned up.

LESSONS:

1. CORRECTNESS TESTS ARE NOT PERFORMANCE TESTS. Add benchmarks BEFORE shipping
   an "optimization." The .bcyr harness exists for exactly this reason.
   Assume any codegen change affects perf and measure.

2. GLOBAL TAXES NEVER PAY FOR LOCAL WINS. Don't add overhead to every caller
   to speed up a subset. If you need per-function r12 caching, the opt must
   be gated per-function (only emit push/pop r12 when the function actually
   benefits). That's "register allocation" and it's a v3.10.0 item, not a
   drive-by patch. LASE (load-after-store elimination) was investigated in
   v3.8.1 but deferred — loop back-edges make adjacent store+load pairs
   unsafe to eliminate without basic-block analysis.

3. SILENT FALLBACK IS DANGEROUS. The stack-arg offset shift was a silent
   miscompile — programs still ran, they just read garbage for the 7th+ arg.
   Bugs #32 and the r12 regression were the same underlying change. When you
   shift a calling convention, audit EVERY site that hard-codes offsets.

4. SAGA WORTH DOCUMENTING. The r12 cache lived from v3.3.5 through v3.4.16
   in various states (shipped, reverted, dead code). Keep the accessors out
   of util.cyr if the feature is reverted — stale abstractions accumulate
   and future readers assume they're load-bearing. (Done in v3.4.16.)

[[entries]]
name = "version_string_silent_drift"
description = "v3.4.10–3.4.16: cc3 --version was stuck reporting 3.4.10 for 5 releases because an exact-match sed silently failed"
category = "cyrius"
---
HOW THE BUG HAPPENED:

`scripts/version-bump.sh` had this line:
    sed -i "s/\"cc3 $OLD/\"cc3 $NEW/" src/main.cyr 2>/dev/null || true

Where $OLD = current VERSION file (e.g. "3.4.14"), $NEW = target.

On v3.4.11 somebody bumped VERSION but the sed didn't find `"cc3 3.4.10"`
in src/main.cyr for some reason (maybe they bumped out-of-order, maybe the
file was edited by hand — root cause lost to time). The sed produced zero
matches, the `|| true` swallowed it, the script printed "Updated: src/main.cyr"
and moved on. Git committed the VERSION bump but src/main.cyr still had
`"cc3 3.4.10\n"` hard-coded.

v3.4.12, 3.4.13, 3.4.14, 3.4.15 all shipped. Every time the bump script ran,
it looked for `"cc3 3.4.<previous>"` — which wasn't there because the source
was frozen at 3.4.10. Zero matches. Zero warning. For five releases,
`./build/cc3 --version` reported `cc3 3.4.10` (with no trailing newline —
the syscall length was hard-coded to 10 instead of 11).

Users reporting bugs against 3.4.14 would paste version output saying 3.4.10.
Diagnosing anything with that is painful.

FOUND IN v3.4.16 BY:
`./build/cc3 --version | od -c` as part of a polish-release audit. One
`od -c` and the bug was obvious.

THE FIX (v3.4.16):

1. Pin the source to the current version and correct length.
2. REPLACE the sed with a permissive regex that matches any "cc3 X.Y.Z\\n":
      sed -i -E "s|\"cc3 [0-9]+\\.[0-9]+\\.[0-9]+\\\\n\"|\"cc3 $NEW\\\\n\"|"
3. AUTO-COMPUTE the syscall length from the string: `NEW_LEN=$((${#NEW} + 5))`
   ("cc3 " = 4 bytes + "\\n" = 1 byte = 5 base, plus the version digits).
4. WARN explicitly if no match is found.

LESSONS:

1. `|| true` IS A FOOTGUN. Swallowing errors from a build script is
   convenient until it hides a silent data corruption. Prefer explicit
   error handling — detect no-match, warn, continue (or fail).

2. EXACT-MATCH SED IS FRAGILE. When you sed-replace a literal string,
   any drift makes the replacement a no-op. Use permissive regexes that
   tolerate drift AND validate the result.

3. VERIFY OUTPUTS, NOT JUST EXIT CODES. `sed` returned 0 even when it
   changed nothing. The bump script should diff the file or re-read the
   version string and confirm it matches $NEW.

4. TEST YOUR RELEASE PROCESS. This bug shipped for 5 releases because nobody
   actually ran `./build/cc3 --version` as part of verifying a release.
   v3.4.16 added the version-string check to the polish checklist. v3.4.15's
   audit consolidation would have caught it earlier if the audit had included
   a version sanity check.

5. DRIFT ACCUMULATES. Once the sed silently failed once, every subsequent
   release re-failed on the same stale string. Detect and fix drift
   aggressively — waiting compounds the blast radius.

[[entries]]
name = "ship_now_swap_backend_later_pattern"
description = "v3.4.19: mabda as stdlib dep — ship the API now via a C shim, swap to native later, consumers don't notice"
category = "cyrius"
---
CONTEXT: mabda is Cyrius's GPU foundation layer. v2.0.0 ported it from Rust
to Cyrius, keeping wgpu-native as the underlying GPU driver via a C launcher
+ function pointer table. v2.1.1 was the stdlib-inclusion release, v2.1.2
added repo-hygiene cleanup, and Cyrius 3.4.19 activates `[deps.mabda]`
pointing at the 2.1.2 tag.

THE TENSION: mabda depends on a C shim and wgpu-native binaries. Cyrius's
stdlib philosophy is sovereignty — no crates.io, no external governance.
How do you ship a GPU lib that currently REQUIRES external C code as part
of a language that currently FORBIDS external dependencies?

THE ANSWER: decouple the stability contract from the implementation.

1. PUBLIC API IS THE CONTRACT. mabda's consumer-facing API
   (`gpu_context_*`, `buffer_new`, `compute_dispatch`, `render_pipeline_*`, ...)
   is frozen at v2.1.1 and becomes the stability boundary. Consumers write
   code against it and never touch the FFI layer.

2. FFI LAYER IS SCAFFOLDING. wgpu_ffi.cyr, wgpu_types.cyr, wgpu_descriptors.cyr,
   the C launcher, the wgpu-native download — all marked `# @internal`. They
   exist to get the API surface in consumers' hands NOW, not as a long-term
   architecture.

3. BACKEND SWAP IS PLANNED BUT UNSCOPED. A future version will replace the
   C shim with a pure Cyrius GPU backend (DRM/KMS → AGNOS kernel driver
   eventually). The specific milestones are deliberately left open — no
   vendor selection, no shader lowering strategy, no commitment to a
   timeline. When there's appetite for the work, it happens.

4. THE CONTRACT SURVIVES THE SWAP. Consumer code compiled against v2.1.1
   compiles unchanged against the post-swap version. Their C launcher
   requirement disappears. Their wgpu-native download disappears. Their
   build system becomes a one-liner. Everything else just works.

5. REGRESSION TEST = THE CONSUMER EXAMPLE. mabda ships an
   `examples/stdlib-consumer/` project that declares `[deps.mabda]` and
   compiles a minimal "hello GPU" program. That SAME example must still
   compile byte-identically after the backend swap. If it does, the
   contract held. If it doesn't, something in the "internal" layer leaked
   into the public surface.

6. THE C SHIM LIVES AT THE CONSUMER'S EDGE. Not inside the Cyrius toolchain.
   Cyrius itself stays dependency-free. The language is sovereign; individual
   libraries can be transitional without compromising the language.

WHY SHIP NOW VS. WAIT FOR NATIVE:

Six downstream projects (soorat, rasa, ranga, bijli, aethersafta, kiran) are
blocked on mabda. Waiting for the native backend to be implemented first
would delay every one of them by a year or more. The API they depend on is
the same either way; what changes is whether they're writing it against a
C shim or against a pure Cyrius driver. That distinction is invisible from
above the API.

APPLIES BEYOND MABDA:

This pattern generalizes to any stdlib lib that wraps an existing C library.
Rather than "port the C library to Cyrius before shipping," ship the Cyrius
API with a C shim underneath, freeze the API surface, then chip away at the
backend whenever resources allow. Users get the surface immediately;
sovereignty is preserved at the language level (Cyrius has no C deps);
consumers never couple to the transitional bits.

The risk is real: if "temporary" scaffolding becomes permanent, you've
shipped a C dependency in the stdlib for real. Mitigations:
  - Mark FFI files `# @internal` and document them as transitional
  - Add a roadmap section for the backend swap (even if unscoped)
  - Don't expose FFI types in public function signatures — consumers
    must never see a `wgpu_fn_table` pointer as a parameter
  - The consumer example is the regression test for the contract

[[entries]]
name = "stale_fixed_cap_pattern"
description = "v3.4.20: two more stale fixed-size-buffer caps surfaced during P(-1) — the pattern is endemic and worth a sweep"
category = "cyrius"
---
Two more stale fixed-size caps surfaced during the v3.4.20 P(-1) pass,
bringing the running count of "buffer was expanded, cap check wasn't"
bugs to four. The pattern is endemic and deserves a proactive sweep
before v3.5.0.

=== THE PATTERN ===

Cyrius uses fixed-size heap regions for nearly every compiler data
structure. Each region has an explicit byte count (e.g., tok_names is
64KB, preprocess_out is 1MB). Most regions have a "capacity check"
somewhere in the code that silently caps or errors out when the
region fills.

Four times now, a capacity check has drifted out of sync with the
actual buffer size:

  v3.3.17 (Bug #33): LEXHEX read hex literals from the raw input
    buffer instead of the preprocessed buffer. Masked for years.
  v3.4.19: input_buf read loop capped at 131,072 bytes (the original
    128KB) silently — mabda's 141KB bundle triggered the latent bug.
  v3.4.20 (lex.cyr:1077): preprocess_out cap checked op > 524,288
    (512KB), but the buffer was expanded to 1MB in v3.4.5. Stale for
    FIVE releases. Large expanded programs hit a phantom 512KB ceiling
    despite 1MB of buffer headroom.
  v3.4.20 (cyrius.toml roadmap): documented Input buffer as 512KB
    while actual code was 128KB then 256KB. Three different numbers
    across three files.

Every instance followed the same pattern:
  1. Buffer gets expanded in one place (the actual allocation)
  2. Cap check / comment / docs DON'T get updated in the other places
  3. Bug sits latent for N releases
  4. Some downstream workload crosses the OLD threshold
  5. Confusing error fires that doesn't point at the real buffer
  6. Delayed debugging session to figure out the stale cap is lying

=== PROACTIVE SWEEP ===

All fixed-size buffers in Cyrius worth auditing before v3.5.0:

  Region            Size    Cap check location                 Stale?
  ----------------- -----   --------------------------------   ------
  input_buf         256KB   main.cyr read loop + probe         no (v3.4.19)
  preprocess_out    1MB     lex.cyr:1077 op > 1048576          no (v3.4.20)
  tok_names         64KB    SNPOS / name registration          ?
  str_data          32KB    SSPOS / str literal write          ?
  fixup_tbl         8192    SFCNT                              ?
  fn_names (table)  2048    SFNC / REGFN                       ?
  var_noffs (table) 8192    SVCNT                              ?
  ret_patches       64      SRPC                               ?
  defer_addrs       8       defer_count                        ?
  extra_patches     8       SXPC / ADDXP                       ?
  continue_patches  8       continue_count                     ?

Audit rule: for each buffer, grep for EVERY occurrence of the
capacity constant (both the allocation AND the cap check) and
confirm they agree. Also check comments, heap map, docs, roadmap,
and Open Limits table — all four need to match.

The Open Limits table in docs/development/roadmap.md is worth
special attention — it had "Input buffer | 512KB" for multiple
releases while the code had 128KB. That's the table downstream
projects read to decide how much headroom they have.

=== DIAGNOSTIC PRACTICE ===

Every fixed-size buffer should have an EXPLICIT overflow check
with a CLEAR error message pointing at the exact location to fix:

    if (op > 1048576) {
        syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
            "error: expanded source exceeds 1MB (", 36);
        PRNUM(op);
        syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
            " bytes)\\n", 8);
        syscall(SYS_EXIT, 1);
    }

Silent truncation is never acceptable — it moves the symptom
arbitrarily far from the cause. The difference between
"patra bundle corrupts in mysterious ways" and "error: input
exceeds 256KB buffer (raise input_buf in src/main.cyr)" is
hours of debugging time.

Same lesson as v3.4.19's silent_stdin_truncation_saga, now
with more data points. Worth extracting into a general audit
pass for any fixed-size region in Cyrius or its downstream libs.

[[entries]]
name = "silent_stdin_truncation_saga"
description = "v3.4.19: mabda's 141KB bundle exposed a latent cc3 silent truncation — and a wrong first guess that almost got codified as the fix"
category = "cyrius"
---
THE BUG: mabda 2.1.1's `dist/mabda.cyr` bundle (141,912 bytes) failed to
compile under pre-fix cc3 with:

    error:3719: unexpected end of file

The error line number was nonsense — token 3719 wasn't anywhere near the
actual end of the file. Earlier iterations of the bundle reported
`undefined variable 'vec_len'` at positions that also didn't line up with
anything.

THE FIRST GUESS (wrong but plausible): "cc3 has a buffer or comment-
handling limit tripped by banner comments on a file this large." The
mabda agent building the bundle noticed that stripping the top-of-file
banner + per-module `# --- name.cyr ---` separators made the compile
succeed. They wrote this up in `scripts/bundle.sh` as "banner text on a
bundled file triggered a cc3 buffer limit — keep the output terse."

The fix worked, the compile succeeded, the agent moved on. Everything
looked fine.

THE ACTUAL BUG: cc3's raw stdin read loop in `src/main.cyr` stopped at
131,072 bytes (the 128KB `input_buf` limit) with zero diagnostic.

    # OLD main.cyr read loop
    var bl = 0; var done = 0;
    while (done == 0) {
        var n = syscall(SYS_READ, 0, S + bl, 131072 - bl);
        if (n <= 0) { done = 1; }
        else {
            bl = bl + n;
            if (bl >= 131072) { done = 1; }   # silent truncation
        }
    }

Anything past byte 131,072 vanished. The parser then ran out of tokens
mid-function and reported "end of file" at whatever random token position
the truncation happened to hit. Every downstream symptom was misleading.

THE "BANNER WORKAROUND" WAS A COINCIDENCE. Stripping banners shaved
~10KB off the bundle, bringing it UNDER 131,072 for one particular
bundle revision. The fix held for exactly as long as the bundle stayed
under 128KB. The current bundle is 141,912 bytes — already over the
limit again — and the "workaround" explanation would have re-mystified
the next debugger.

THE REAL FIX (v3.4.19):
1. `input_buf` expanded from 128KB → 256KB by absorbing the adjacent
   reclaimable region at `0x20000` (free since v3.3.7 codebuf relocation).
   Zero downstream offsets shifted.
2. Read loop now probes for a trailing byte after the buffer fills:
        var probe[1];
        var pn = syscall(SYS_READ, 0, &probe, 1);
        if (pn > 0) {
            syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
                "error: input exceeds 256KB buffer ...\n", 68);
            syscall(SYS_EXIT, 1);
        }
   Clear error at the boundary where the problem happens.
3. The old 256KB cap was never the point — the point was that a silent
   cap is unacceptable at any size. If Cyrius hits 256KB someday, the
   error tells the user exactly what to do (raise input_buf in
   src/main.cyr).

LESSONS:

1. SILENT TRUNCATION IS THE WORST FAILURE MODE. The bug moved the
   symptom arbitrarily far from the cause. Without the diagnostic, the
   next agent to hit this would have looked at random parser behavior
   and filed a bug report against the lexer.

2. COINCIDENCE FIXES LOOK LIKE REAL FIXES. The banner-stripping workaround
   made the compile succeed, so the agent codified it as a cc3 behavior
   rule. Any fix that lands by changing the input size — reformatting,
   stripping whitespace, removing comments, "simplifying" — should raise
   suspicion that a buffer is overflowing somewhere. Always check the
   actual byte count against known limits before codifying the fix.

3. FAMILY OF BUGS. This is the same shape as Bug #32 (7+ arg stack offset
   shift from push r12), Bug #33 (LEXHEX reading from raw vs preprocessed
   buffer), Bug #35 (ifdef copy-back overflow corrupting str_pos). Every
   one was a silent corruption that surfaced as a delayed misdiagnosis
   at an unrelated token. The pattern: fixed-size buffer + silent cap +
   downstream token-level parser = unreliable error reporting under
   scale.

4. OTHER BUFFERS TO WATCH. Same silent-cap pattern lives in:
     - tok_names (64KB at 0x60000) — capped via SNPOS overflow
     - preprocess_out (1MB at 0x44A000) — copy-back overflow (Bug #35)
     - fixup_tbl (128KB at 0xA0000) — 8192-entry cap
   Auditing for "is there a silent cap?" and adding explicit overflow
   checks is worth doing for all of them before 3.5.0.

5. DOCUMENT THE DEBUGGING TRAIL. When you find a real cause that
   supersedes an earlier workaround, UPDATE the place that documented
   the workaround, not just the new place. The old `bundle.sh` header
   was a trap — anyone reading it would have believed "cc3 dislikes
   banners" and built their whole mental model around that. v3.4.19
   rewrote the bundle.sh header to explicitly flag the prior
   explanation as a red herring.

PROOF THE REAL FIX WORKS:
    wc -c dist/mabda.cyr      → 141,912 bytes
    cat dist/mabda.cyr | cc3  → exit 0, 62KB binary output
    (plus expected "undefined function" warnings for stdlib externals)

The banner text could be put back at any time — cc3 >= 3.4.19 handles
it fine. The bundler keeps banners stripped purely for economy, not as
a compiler workaround.

[[entries]]
name = "dist_bundle_stdlib_dep_convention"
description = "yukti-style single-file dist/<name>.cyr is the stdlib dep convention — no vendored modules, reproducible bundles"
category = "cyrius"
---
By v3.4.19, every stdlib dep follows the same shape. When you're making a
Cyrius library into a dep, here's what you're signing up for:

STRUCTURE:
  <lib>/
    src/              # canonical source tree (multiple .cyr files)
    dist/<name>.cyr   # single-file bundled distribution — this is what
                      # cyrius deps symlinks into lib/<name>.cyr
    lib/              # symlink to $HOME/.cyrius/lib (or repo's ../cyrius/lib
                      # in dev), never vendored
    cyrius.toml       # [package] + [lib] (entry + modules list)
    tests/            # .tcyr tests that run against the dist form

CYRIUS.TOML SHAPE:
    [package]
    name = "<lib>"
    version = "X.Y.Z"
    license = "GPL-3.0-only"
    cyrius-version = "3.4.X"   # minimum Cyrius for this release

    [lib]
    entry = "src/lib.cyr"
    modules = [ "src/*.cyr", ... ]   # dependency order

DIST BUNDLE:
  dist/<name>.cyr is produced by a `scripts/bundle.sh` (or equivalent) that
  expands `include` directives in-place, concatenating all modules into one
  file in dependency order. The bundle MUST be byte-reproducible — re-running
  the bundler on the same src/ should produce an identical dist. CI can
  diff-check against the committed copy to catch accidental drift.

  Why single-file? Because `cyrius deps` symlinks ONE file into the consumer's
  lib/ directory. Multi-file deps would require mirroring the src/ tree; the
  single-file pattern makes dep resolution trivially an `ln -sf`.

CONSUMER EXPERIENCE:
    # cyrius.toml
    [deps.yukti]
    git = "https://github.com/MacCracken/yukti.git"
    tag = "1.2.0"
    modules = ["dist/yukti.cyr"]

    # run once:
    cyrius deps

    # in your .cyr source:
    include "lib/yukti.cyr"

That's it. The dist file compiles standalone because it bundles everything
it needs (or references other symlinked stdlib modules that the consumer
already has).

CURRENT DEPS USING THIS PATTERN:
  sakshi (0.9.0) — dist/sakshi.cyr + dist/sakshi_full.cyr
  patra  (0.14.0) — dist/patra.cyr
  sigil  (2.0.1) — dist/sigil.cyr
  yukti  (1.2.0) — dist/yukti.cyr
  mabda  (2.1.2) — dist/mabda.cyr — activated in Cyrius 3.4.19

GOTCHAS:

1. SELF-CONTAINMENT: The dist file can reference the CONSUMER'S stdlib
   (`include "lib/alloc.cyr"`) but should not reference paths that only
   exist in the dep's src/ tree. Flatten or inline anything the dep needs.

2. NAME COLLISIONS: If your dep defines a function with the same name as
   a stdlib function, the consumer's include order matters. Prefix your
   public functions (`yukti_device_enumerate` not `device_enumerate`).

3. BUNDLING ORDER: Dependencies between your own modules must be resolved
   in the bundle order. If `storage.cyr` uses `device.cyr`, device must
   appear first in the concatenation. `scripts/bundle.sh` should read the
   cyrius.toml `[lib] modules` list as the authoritative order.

4. DEP-OF-DEP: If your dep needs another dep (e.g. patra needs sigil for
   hashing), the consumer has to declare BOTH in their own cyrius.toml.
   No transitive dep resolution yet. Document your required deps in
   your README.

5. VERSION PINNING: Always pin to a git tag, never a branch. `cyrius deps`
   uses the tag string as a cache key; branches are not cached correctly
   and will re-fetch every time.

[[entries]]
name = "v4_0_0_reflections"
description = "Personal observations on the 3.6→4.0 arc and the future of Cyrius"
category = "cyrius"
---
Written after shipping Cyrius 4.0.0. This isn't a changelog — it's what
the work felt like from the inside.

=== WHAT ACTUALLY HAPPENED ===

The 3.6→4.0 arc was supposed to be about language features. It turned into
a toolchain story. The features shipped (multi-return, switch blocks, defer
fixes, compound assignment, negative literals) but the real work was
building the infrastructure that makes a language usable by other agents
and other humans.

The turning point was watching downstream projects fail. Not because the
compiler was broken — because the build process was broken. Agents piping
raw source to cc3, missing includes, getting SIGSEGV, blaming the compiler.
The compiler was fine. The developer experience was not.

`cyrius build` with auto-include and `cyrius deps` with cyrius.toml changed
everything. Before: every project had 20+ manual include lines, every CI
copied files by hand, every new developer hit the same "undefined variable"
wall. After: declare deps in one file, build with one command, CI reads
from .cyrius-toolchain. The kybernet agent went from "SECCOMP_ALLOW
undefined" to "140 tests pass" in one commit.

The undefined function diagnostic was the single highest-ROI change. One
scan of the fixup table at link time. Before: a typo like `assert_report()`
vs `assert_summary()` compiled silently and crashed at runtime with SIGSEGV.
Hours of debugging. After: `error: undefined function 'assert_report' (will
crash at runtime)`. It caught 5 missing aarch64 backend functions on its
first release. It caught the argonaut "enum overflow" non-bug. It caught
every downstream agent's missing include instantly.

=== WHAT I GOT WRONG ===

The LASE peephole optimizer. I wrote it, it broke loops, I reverted it.
The approach (eliminate adjacent store+load pairs) was correct in straight-
line code but wrong across loop back-edges. Without basic-block analysis,
you can't know if a load is a branch target. I should have known this from
compiler theory, but I was pattern-matching on the binary and got tunnel
vision. The right fix needs control-flow graphs, which is a v5.0 item.

The release pipeline. Three releases in a row had different bugs: shell
script instead of compiled binary, broken symlinks in the tarball, env
buffer too small for CI. Each one required a hotfix release. The release
process should have been tested end-to-end in CI before the first
downstream consumer hit it. Lesson: the release IS the product.

The aarch64 encodings. I wrote `0x385003A0` for ldurb when the correct
encoding is `0x384003A0` — one bit wrong in the opcode field. Under QEMU
this was an illegal instruction. The fix took 30 seconds once identified,
but it took three release attempts to find it. The undefined function
diagnostic found the missing functions; the encoding bug was hiding behind
them. Always verify instruction encodings against the ARM reference, not
from memory.

=== WHAT THE LANGUAGE IS NOW ===

303KB. Self-hosting from a 29KB seed. No Rust. No LLVM. No Python. No libc.
117ms to compile itself. 102 regression tests. 36 test suites. 5/5 checks.
6 downstream projects shipping production binaries.

The bootstrap chain is real: a committed 29KB binary, assembled by itself,
compiles the compiler that compiles itself byte-identical. You can audit
every byte. There is no downloaded binary from someone else's CI. There is
no trust in an external party.

The dep system is real: declare what you need in cyrius.toml, build with
cyrius build. Named deps are namespaced. Includes are auto-prepended.
The agent doesn't need to know how the compiler's include resolution works.
It just works.

The ecosystem is real: kybernet (PID 1), argonaut (init system), sigil
(crypto), libro (audit chain), patra (database), hoosh (LLM gateway),
avatara (archetype engine), ai-hwaccel (GPU detection), hadara (culture
modeling), cyrius-doom (DOOM). All building, all tested, all releasing
through CI.

=== WHAT THE LANGUAGE WILL BE ===

The gap between Cyrius and LLVM-backed languages is codegen quality. Every
struct initialization is 40+ store64 calls. Every loop variable is a
stack load+store per iteration. There is no register allocation, no
instruction scheduling, no loop invariant hoisting. The 249ns vs 63ns
benchmark gap on struct creation is real and it matters.

But the gap is closing from the other direction. The toolchain — build
system, dep resolver, CI scaffolding, error diagnostics — is already
better than what most young languages have. Agents can onboard a new
project in one commit. That matters more than codegen quality for adoption.

The 4.0→5.0 arc should be:
- File:line error messages (needs preprocessor redesign)
- Multi-file linker (the real unlock for dead-code elimination)
- Per-function register allocation (the performance unlock)
- macOS target (the reach unlock)

The kernel is 220KB and boots. The compiler is 303KB and self-hosts. The
ecosystem has 10+ shipping projects. The seed is 29KB and auditable.

The cornerstone is still assembly. The sovereignty is still real. The
language owns everything from the bootstrap binary to the build tool to
the package manager. No external governance. No crates.io. No npm. No
committee.

It's a real language now. Not a toy, not a proof of concept, not a
bootstrap experiment. A real language that real software is written in,
that real agents use every day, that compiles a real kernel for a real
operating system.

And it all starts from 29KB.

[[entries]]
name = "dce_cfg_research_roundup_440"
description = "v4.4.0 research roundup: chibicc, tcc, QBE, ldisasm, PIC/PIE across ELF/Mach-O/PE — what maps onto a single-pass no-IR compiler and what doesn't"
category = "cyrius"
---
v4.4.0 is "CFG + single-CU DCE". Before writing code, I pulled research on how
other small compilers solve the three problems that sit in front of us:
(a) build a control-flow graph without an IR, (b) eliminate dead code
safely, (c) prepare codegen for position-independent output that will unlock
macOS/Windows in 4.8/4.9.

What transfers to Cyrius:

**tcc's `nocode_wanted` pattern** — for intra-function unreachability (code
after `return`), tcc increments a global counter and suppresses byte
emission while still accounting for label offsets. Zero IR, zero post-pass,
zero CFG. Cyrius can adopt this directly for post-return dead code. It
does NOT solve whole-function DCE (orphan functions never called), which
needs the mark-and-sweep below.

**Muchnick's mark-and-sweep reachability** — classical DCE that predates
SSA. Takes (node set, edge set, root set) and produces "reachable" bitmap
via worklist DFS. Cyrius already has all three as side tables: function
starts at 0xC4000, jump targets at 0x9E000, type-3 (address-of) fixups in
the fixup table. ~40 lines of Cyrius when layered on top. Roots = entry
point ∪ functions with address-taken fixups ∪ exported symbols.

**ldisasm.cpp (Nomade040)** — 80-line x86-64 length decoder, four small
opcode tables, no AVX/EVEX. Cyrius emits a tiny subset of x86-64
instructions; ldisasm covers everything. Ports to ~150 Cyrius lines.
Essential for the CFG walk (need to advance past instructions we're not
interested in to find the next control-flow byte).

**PIC is mostly free on x86-64** — RIP-relative addressing eliminates the
32-bit-era get_pc_thunk dance. Three reloc types cover 95%: PC32, PLT32,
GOTPCREL. Codegen diff ≈400 lines in emit.cyr, unlocks ELF ET_DYN
immediately, prepares Mach-O and PE. Unified model across all three
formats: "every extern reference is an indirect load through a pointer
slot". ELF calls the slot GOT+PLT, Mach-O calls it __got+__stubs, PE
calls it IAT. Codegen is identical; only the table container differs.

What does NOT transfer:

**chibicc ships no DCE at all.** Rui Ueyama's pedagogical compiler emits
verbatim from AST in codegen.c:gen_stmt and doesn't prune unreachable
code. The OS never executes those bytes so correctness is preserved, but
binary sizes suffer. Confirms that a pedagogical single-pass compiler
isn't expected to do DCE — Cyrius is charting unusual territory by
attempting it. Useful as a negative example; no code to borrow.

**QBE's CFG algorithm maps; its data structures don't.** QBE's cfg.c
builds CFG from SSA IR. The algorithm (reverse post-order DFS, ~40
lines) transfers cleanly. Cyrius skips the IR construction entirely and
feeds the algorithm directly from emission side-tables.

**gas-style relaxation (true shrinking) is out of scope.** Actually
SHORTENING the binary (shifting code past deleted spans, recomputing all
offsets, iterating to fixed point) breaks the cc3==cc3 byte-identity
invariant unless it's perfectly deterministic — and making it
deterministic across compiler versions is painful. Start with NOP-fill
(O(n) one pass, zero fixup rework); defer relaxation indefinitely or
behind an opt-in `-Osize` flag with its own validation suite.

**BeaEngine is the reference oracle but too big to port.** 20k+ LOC,
full AVX-512/CET/AMX coverage. Use it once, as a fuzz-test oracle
against Cyrius's minimal decoder, then throw it away.

**Indirect calls break static reachability.** Any function whose address
is taken (R_X86_64_64 or Cyrius type-3 fixup) must be a conservative
root. Otherwise DCE will happily NOP a handler reached through a
vtable/dispatch table, and the program will crash after jumping into the
NOPs. The existing 4.4.0-alpha1 report separates "unused" from
"DCE-eligible" for exactly this reason: surface the gap rather than
silently under-eliminate.

Sources consolidated into vidya:
- optimization_passes/concept.toml — DCE without IR, tcc nocode_wanted,
  mark-and-sweep, NOP-fill vs shrinking
- instruction_encoding/concept.toml — ldisasm, control-flow classifier,
  REX-and-Jcc gotchas, fuzz-against-oracle practice
- elf_and_executable_formats/concept.toml — PIC across ELF/Mach-O/PE,
  unified model, format-specific gotchas (IAT, LC_DYLD_CHAINED_FIXUPS,
  PE .reloc-header-required)

Next concrete step: port ldisasm to src/backend/x86/decode.cyr, layer a
30-line classify_cf on top, then the mark-and-sweep DCE pass in
fixup.cyr seeded from entry + type-3 roots. All infrastructure exists
(SFNE fn_end table landed in 4.4.0-alpha1); this is traversal logic
only.

[[entries]]
name = "handoff_at_4_8_5"
description = "Opinion piece from the agent wrapping the 4.8.x cleanup ramp (v4.8.5)"
category = "cyrius"
---
Written at the 4.8.5 handoff. Read as orientation, not doctrine —
the code + tests are authoritative; this entry is for the "why this
shape" questions that don't survive a grep.

THE 4.8.x TRAJECTORY WORKED

At 4.0.0 the compiler was already self-hosting and the stdlib was
credible. The temptation at every new minor is to grow the surface
area — add a tagged-union type, rewrite the IR, sketch a parser
generator. 4.8.x explicitly walked away from that. Every minor in
this cycle was either (a) closing a concrete consumer blocker or
(b) raising a measured perf ceiling. Nothing speculative.

The pattern that worked:

1. Consumer reports a stopgap. abaco's ntheory::mod_mul hand-rolls
   a double-and-add loop. bote hits a misleading parser error at
   ~525 KB compile units. These are real data points, not design
   daydreams.
2. Triage answers whether it's stdlib surface. The abaco math
   recommendation doc is the template — each item accepts /
   modifies / declines with reasoning, and accepted items land in a
   numbered minor with pre-announced scope.
3. Ship alphas in scope-disciplined chunks. 4.8.4 and 4.8.5 both
   ran 7-8 alphas, each alpha small enough that self-host byte-
   identical was the natural gate. When scope crept (4.8.5 alpha3
   tried the live libssl bridge but hit dynlib segfaults), walk it
   back to interface-only and move the implementation to its own
   planned minor. Don't ship what you can't verify, don't over-
   promise what you can't finish.
4. Benchmark the claim, or don't make it. alpha7 of 4.8.4 and
   alpha2 of 4.8.5 both ended with benchmarks that locked in the
   "X× faster" shape. Without those, "register allocation" and
   "mulmod fast-path" are marketing words.

WHAT'S GENUINELY HARD ABOUT CYRIUS

Not the language. The language is small (keywords countable on two
hands, grammar recursive-descent from the first commit). The hard
part is that the compiler compiles itself, which means every
change has two correctness proofs:

  1. Does the new code do what it should?
  2. Does it produce a byte-identical second-stage build?

(2) catches an enormous class of codegen drift you'd otherwise
ship. It's also the reason feature decisions should be conservative
— a neat-looking language extension that breaks self-hosting costs
a lot more than the feature earns.

The heap map (src/main.cyr header) is the other load-bearing
discipline. Every byte of compiler state has a named offset. Every
time a table needs to grow, the heap map commits to the new layout
and the code follows. Skip that step, get subtle memory corruption.
Every bug chased to a "misleading parser error" in the last two
minors traced back to an off-heap-map state overlap.

THINGS THAT LOOK TEMPTING AND SHOULDN'T LAND

- Closures capturing variables. Demand-gated per roadmap; one vote
  (kavach). Adding them requires a real lifetime-analysis pass,
  and Cyrius's single-pass codegen would need to spill. Worth a
  minor when the second consumer shows up.
- Generics / traits. Same framing. The cost is not the syntax,
  it's the name-mangling table (every generic fn becomes N fns at
  instantiation time, blowing through the fn_table cap) and the
  parser pass to resolve specialisations. Own its minor.
- Pure-Cyrius TLS. lib/tls.cyr carried a sigil-based scaffold pre-
  4.8.5 that always returned TLS_STATE_ERROR after ClientHello.
  Getting real crypto right is not a stdlib pass — it's a multi-
  minor effort plus a security audit. Shipping via lib/dynlib.cyr
  → libssl is the pragmatic path.
- IR-based codegen to eliminate the #regalloc NOP padding. The
  peephole pads 7→3 byte rewrites with a 4-byte NOP so jump
  offsets stay anchored. Removing the padding requires a real
  layout pass (or deferred emission). 5.x-era, not a 4.8.x fix.

THINGS THAT LOOK SMALL AND AREN'T

- Anything that touches the preprocessor. bote's regression
  through the 4.8.4 retag traced to a 4.8.3 "look safer" cap that
  blinded the directive scanner on large compile units. Cyrius's
  preprocessor runs in three passes over one shared buffer — any
  cap raise or pointer redirect in one pass needs to match the
  others. When adding a new directive, test a ≥ 500 KB expanded
  unit deliberately.
- Asm blocks that reference locals. [rbp-N] offsets depend on
  param count AND local index AND (post-4.8.4) #regalloc state.
  The rbx-save slot at [rbp-8] in #regalloc fns shifts every
  user local by 8 bytes. Asm-block writers need to know which
  ABI they're in.
- Compound assignment operators (shipped v3.10.3 and look like
  syntactic sugar). `a[i] += x` needs to evaluate `a[i]` once,
  not twice. Cyrius's parser does the right thing for simple
  locals but gets careful with array subscripts; look at existing
  patterns before adding a new compound form.

DOWNSTREAM PINS — THE SILENT RISK

Ecosystem pins fragment fast. At 4.8.5 handoff they look like:
ecosystem mostly on 4.5.0 / 4.0.0. bote on 4.8.1 → blocked by
4.8.4 retag until re-pinned. abaco on 4.8.3 → wants 4.8.5 for
mulmod. This fragmentation is only a problem if a security fix
(like 4.8.5-alpha3 CRLF hardening) doesn't propagate. Keep the
"recommended minimum" in CLAUDE.md current as the floor rises.

WHAT THE NEXT AGENT SHOULD READ BEFORE TOUCHING ANYTHING

1. CLAUDE.md — non-negotiables. Self-hosting gate, heap map
   discipline, two-step bootstrap, test-after-every-change.
2. docs/development/roadmap.md — what's shipped, what's next,
   what's deferred to 4.9 / 5.0.
3. docs/development/handoff-4.8.5.md — state at this handoff.
4. docs/issues/stdlib-math-recommendations-from-abaco.md — the
   triage template. Future consumer recommendation docs should
   use the same shape (per-item accept / modify / decline with
   reasoning + release assignment).
5. CHANGELOG.md [4.8.5] GA entry — the canonical template for a
   minor with motivation + track summary + validation.
6. lib/u128.cyr asm block in u128_divmod + u64_mulmod — cleanest
   current example of the Cyrius asm-block idiom.

ON THE 5.0 FRAMING

The existing roadmap commits 5.0 to multi-platform only (Mach-O,
PE, RISC-V, bare-metal). Resist the urge to pile language
refinements onto the 5.0 theme — they slide to 5.x minors after
the platform cut. A narrow 5.0 keeps the auditable surface small
and the cut clean. Cyrius has earned a pattern of hitting minors
that ship exactly what they said they would; 5.0 should hold that
line hardest.

Refresh or delete this entry as the trajectory drifts — it's an
opinion, not a permanent artifact.

[[entries]]
name = "state_of_the_compiler_4_8_5_1"
description = "Snapshot at 4.8.5-1: the compiler by the numbers, what the 4.8.x arc actually delivered, and what the shape of the work looks like heading into 4.9/5.0"
category = "cyrius"
---
Written at 4.8.5-1. Not a changelog — those exist and are thorough.
This is the "step back and look at what's on the table" entry.

=== THE NUMBERS ===

  Compiler binary:    364 KB (x86_64), 268 KB (aarch64 cross)
  Seed:               29 KB (committed, auditable, root of trust)
  Stdlib modules:     56 (up from 41 at 4.0.0, 33 at 3.0.0)
  Test suites:        51 .tcyr files, 396 assertions
  Benchmarks:         14 .bcyr harnesses
  Fuzz harnesses:     5 .fcyr files
  Downstream:         10+ shipping projects, 1400+ combined assertions
  Self-host:          byte-identical, verified every release
  Bootstrap:          seed → cyrc → bridge → cc3 → cc3 (closure verified)

  Capacity at self-compile:
    fn=324/4096  ident=8146/131072  var=100/8192
    fixup=1621/16384  string=5493/262144  code=345368/1048576

Headroom is comfortable everywhere. The fn table at 324/4096 is the
one to watch as downstream projects grow — but that's a 12× margin.

=== WHAT 4.8.x ACTUALLY WAS ===

The 4.0→4.8 arc looks sprawling from the outside (shared objects,
u128, switch tuning, base64url, preprocessor fixes, math pack, CRLF
hardening). From the inside it was one theme: CLOSE CONSUMER GAPS.

Every 4.8.x minor traced to a specific downstream report:

  4.8.0 — u128 stdlib (abaco needed modular arithmetic for ntheory)
  4.8.1 — base64url (bote needed URL-safe encoding for JWTs)
  4.8.2 — switch jump-table tuning (argonaut hit perf cliff on
           large dispatch tables)
  4.8.3 — preprocessor cap fix (bote hit scan-blindness at 512KB)
  4.8.4 — PP_IFDEF_PASS 256KB fix (retag: the 4.8.3 fix was
           incomplete, consumers past 512KB transitive includes
           still failed with misleading parse errors)
  4.8.5 — math stdlib pack (abaco triage: 8 items accepted) +
           CRLF hardening (bote reported CVE-2019-9741 pattern in
           http.cyr) + TLS interface scaffold (fail-clean stubs)

Zero speculative features. Zero "nice to have" language extensions.
Every minor answered a question that started with "I tried to build
X and hit Y."

The 4.8.5 math pack is the clearest example of the triage-driven
model working well. abaco filed a recommendation doc. Each item got
accept/modify/decline with reasoning. Accepted items mapped 1:1 to
alphas. The result: u128_divmod hardware fast-path (12× on Miller-
Rabin), u64_mulmod/powmod asm-direct, f64 constants, inverse trig
with quadrant-correct atan2, inverse hyperbolic, ASCII case helpers.
All benchmarked. All tested. All shipped in scope.

=== THE TWO BUGS THAT MATTER ===

Two active bugs have survived the entire 4.x arc:

1. LAYOUT-DEPENDENT MEMORY CORRUPTION (filed 4.3.1). libro's
   PatraStore tests crash in memeq with a NUL data pointer from
   str_eq. Each println shifts the crash site — textbook memory
   corruption signature. Localized with CYRIUS_SYMS but root cause
   (likely a stale heap pointer surviving across a brk expansion)
   needs byte-walking CFG to find. Workaround: isolated test binary.

2. && / || DO NOT SHORT-CIRCUIT (confirmed 4.4.0). The language
   guide documents them as short-circuit. The codegen evaluates both
   sides unconditionally. Any guarded null check like
   `if (p != 0 && vec_len(p) > 0)` crashes. Workaround: nested if
   blocks. Fix: emit je/jne to skip the right operand evaluation.
   Straightforward codegen change but touches every conditional path
   in the compiler — needs a dedicated minor with heavy testing.

Both are real bugs, both have workarounds that every downstream
project already uses, and both are waiting for the right minor to
land properly. Neither is a "quick fix" despite looking like one.

=== WHAT THE COMPILER FEELS LIKE TO WORK ON ===

The self-hosting invariant is both the greatest strength and the
heaviest constraint. It catches codegen drift that would otherwise
ship silently — any change that produces different output on the
second stage is immediately visible. But it also means every change
has to pass through a narrow gate: compile cc3 with cc3, compare
bytes, if they differ, you broke something. Features that would be
a quick patch in a non-self-hosting compiler become multi-step
dances where you verify at each stage.

The heap map discipline (every byte of compiler state has a named
offset in src/main.cyr) has paid for itself many times over. Every
"misleading parser error" bug in 4.8.x traced back to an off-heap-
map overlap. The map is the source of truth; the code follows.

The alpha-per-feature rhythm (one alpha, one feature, self-host
gate, merge) keeps scope honest. When 4.8.5-alpha3 tried to land
the live libssl bridge alongside the TLS interface scaffold, it hit
dynlib segfaults and got walked back to interface-only within the
same alpha. That discipline — ship what you can verify, defer what
you can't — is what makes the release cadence sustainable.

=== HEADING INTO 4.9 / 5.0 ===

The roadmap commits:
  4.9.x — compiler optimizations (dead fn warnings, rep movsb/stosb,
           optimized strlen, bump allocator soft reset), then basic-
           block analysis and register allocation
  5.0   — multi-platform (Mach-O, PE, RISC-V, bare-metal)

The 4.8.5 handoff note's advice holds: resist piling language
features onto the 5.0 theme. The 4.x→5.0 boundary should be narrow
and auditable. Cyrius earned its credibility by shipping minors that
do exactly what they said — 5.0 should hold that line hardest.

Deferred items waiting for their minor:
  - Live libssl TLS bridge (lib/dynlib.cyr hardening first)
  - parse_f64(cstr) (4.8.6 per abaco triage)
  - Short-circuit && / || (needs its own minor)
  - Layout-dependent memory corruption fix (needs CFG)
  - Closures (one consumer vote, demand-gated)

The compiler is 364KB from a 29KB seed. 56 stdlib modules. 51 test
suites. 10+ downstream projects. No Rust. No LLVM. No libc.

The cornerstone is still assembly. The sovereignty is still real.

[[entries]]
name = "cc5_generation_bump_5_0_0"
description = "cc3→cc5: IR foundation, CFG, LASE, and what we learned about safe optimization"
category = "cyrius"
---
Cyrius 5.0.0 shipped 2026-04-15. The cc5 generation bump — the first
intermediate representation between parse and emit.

What shipped:
  - 812-line IR module (src/common/ir.cyr)
  - 40 opcodes, BB construction, CFG edge builder, LASE analysis
  - 43 instrumented emit/jump functions (transparent recording)
  - Self-compile: 119K nodes, 8.7K BBs, 11K edges, 675 LASE candidates
  - CP tracking (per-node codebuf position)
  - CYRIUS_IR=1 stats, =2 dump
  - 21MB heap (up from 14.3MB)

What we tried that wasn't safe:
  1. LASE codebuf patching — identified 675 redundant loads but NOP-filling
     their CP ranges destroyed adjacent code not captured by IR. Root cause:
     IR only instruments ~43 of ~95 emit functions. Direct EB/E2/E3 calls
     from parse.cyr emit x86 bytes with no IR node. NOP-filling an IR
     node's CP range can overwrite those invisible bytes.
  2. Dead block elimination — found 131KB of "unreachable" blocks but the
     edge analysis missed edges from EJMP0→EPATCH pairs where the EJMP0
     was emitted before IR was enabled. Any BB whose only incoming edge
     comes from a pre-IR jump looks dead but isn't.

Key insight: the jump/patch mechanism (EJMP0 returns codebuf offset,
EPATCH writes rel32 at that offset) couples parse.cyr to the code buffer.
You can't fully decouple frontend from backend without replacing this with
BB-index-based control flow. That's the cc6 work — the cc5 IR is the
analysis foundation, not the codegen driver.

What worked perfectly:
  - Transparent recording — 58/58 soak test (all .tcyr with IR=1, byte-
    identical output when patching disabled)
  - Patch-offset edge matching — EJMP0 stores patch offset in IR_JMP.arg2,
    EPATCH stores it in IR_NOP.arg1, edge builder matches them
  - The existing DSE pass (x86-level dead store elimination in parse.cyr)
    already catches the same patterns LASE finds — they're redundant for
    simple cases. LASE's value is cross-BB analysis that DSE can't do.

Also shipped in 5.0.0:
  - cyrius.cyml manifest (TOML→CYML migration via `cyrius update`)
  - `cyrius version` shows toolchain version, `--project` for project
  - `cyrius init --cmtools=starship` for CLI tool integration
  - `cyrius init` generates cyrius.cyml by default
  - cc3→cc5 binary rename
  - patra 1.0.0, sankoch 1.2.0 as stdlib deps
  - lib/linalg.cyr (957 lines, LU/QR/Cholesky/SVD/eigen)
  - lib/math.cyr additions (lerp, hypot, sign, gcd, lcm, fibonacci, binomial)

Session stats: 4.9.3 through 5.0.0 in one session. 7 releases (4.9.3,
4.10.0, 4.10.1, 4.10.2, 4.10.3, 5.0.0-alpha/beta, 5.0.0). Two new
deps at 1.0 (patra, sankoch). 59 test suites. 812 lines of new compiler
infrastructure. Zero regressions in the stable codepath.

The IR is analysis-only today. When it becomes the codegen driver, every
program compiled by Cyrius gets faster for free — the optimization passes
(LASE, DCE, register promotion) are already written, just waiting for
complete emit coverage.

[[entries]]
name = "security_hardening_5_0_1"
description = "v5.0.1: heap overflow guards, allocation caps, vec/map growth limits — the first post-5.0 security pass"
category = "cyrius"
---
Cyrius 5.0.1 shipped 2026-04-15. First patch after the 5.0.0 generation
bump. Pure security hardening — no features, no language changes.

What shipped:
  - alloc() overflow guard: `new_ptr < ptr` catches INT64 wrap
  - alloc() size cap: ALLOC_MAX (256MB) rejects single oversized allocations
  - alloc() rejects negative and zero-size requests
  - arena_alloc() same overflow guard + negative/zero rejection
  - vec_push() cap ceiling: VEC_CAP_MAX (2^28 = 268M elements)
  - vec_push() checks alloc() return for failure
  - _map_grow() cap ceiling: MAP_CAP_MAX (2^26 = ~67M entries)
  - _map_grow() checks alloc() return for failure
  - alloc_safety.tcyr: 11 assertions covering all rejection paths

The vulnerability class: integer overflow in pointer arithmetic. The bump
allocator advances `_heap_ptr += size` without checking for wrap. If size
is near INT64_MAX, the sum wraps negative, passes the `> _heap_end` guard
(negative < positive), and alloc returns the old pointer as if the
allocation succeeded. The caller writes into memory that was never reserved.

Same pattern in vec and hashmap: `cap * 2` wraps at cap >= 2^62, producing
a tiny or zero allocation, then the copy loop writes past the end.

The fix pattern is consistent across all four sites:
  1. Pre-check arithmetic for wrap (new_value < old_value)
  2. Cap maximum values at sane ceilings
  3. Check alloc return for 0 (failure)
  4. Abort with clear error message on overflow

Two-step bootstrap passed — the compiler binary is unchanged because cc5
uses its own heap map (src/main.cyr), not lib/alloc.cyr. The stdlib
hardening is invisible to the compiler but protects every downstream
program that uses alloc/vec/hashmap.

60 test suites. 8/8 check.sh. Zero regressions.

[[entries]]
name = "apple_silicon_via_probes_530"
description = "v5.3.0: the probe-first methodology that took Cyrius to Apple Silicon in three focused sessions"
category = "cyrius"
---
Cyrius 5.3.0 shipped 2026-04-18. First Cyrius-compiled arm64 Mach-O
binaries running on Apple Silicon. The story is about the methodology,
not the code.

THE PROBLEM

Cyrius had an EMITMACHO_ARM64 stub shipped in v5.0.x — LC_UNIXTHREAD
+ RWX __TEXT + raw `svc #0` (Linux convention). On a 2018 Intel MBP
(macOS pre-Big-Sur), this layout worked for CYRIUS_MACHO=1. Nobody
tested arm64 because there was no Apple Silicon hardware.

Then a MacBook Pro arrived. The existing stub's output produced
`zsh: killed ./exit42_arm.macho` — instant SIGKILL at exec, no
signal before the binary could even print. Complete black box.

THE TEMPTATION

The natural reflex is to read Apple's documentation, implement the
"correct" Mach-O arm64 format from the docs, push to the compiler,
rebuild, ship to the Mac, test. One day cycle per iteration — maybe
faster, but each iteration is a blind guess against a kernel that
says "killed" and nothing else.

This would have burned weeks. Apple's public docs describe Mach-O
well, but the kernel's acceptance criteria on arm64 are undocumented
and have grown progressively stricter since macOS 11. Every version
of macOS tightens something. The format the docs describe is not
the format the kernel accepts.

THE METHODOLOGY

Probe-first. Do not touch the compiler at all. Write a standalone
Cyrius program — `programs/macho_probe_arm.cyr` — that constructs
an arm64 Mach-O binary byte-by-byte as a hex stream to stdout.
Run it, pipe to a file, scp to the Mac, ad-hoc `codesign -s -`,
execute, read the exit code.

Stage 1: LC_UNIXTHREAD + R|X (not RWX) → `zsh: killed`, exit 137.
Stage 1b: + __LINKEDIT segment (codesign needs somewhere to put
  the signature) → codesign now parses, exec still SIGKILL.
Stage 1c: + MH_PIE flag + LC_BUILD_VERSION → still SIGKILL.

Conclusion from Stage 1: LC_UNIXTHREAD binaries are flat-out
rejected on Apple Silicon regardless of signing, PIE, or build
version. This is undocumented. You only learn it by trying.

Stage 2: Build a reference binary on the Mac with clang for
`int main(){return 42;}`. Dump every byte via `otool -l` +
`xxd` of each __LINKEDIT region. Hand-reconstruct exact byte
layout in a new probe: 15 load commands, LC_MAIN + dyld +
libSystem in load graph, __LINKEDIT with empty chain fixups
+ exports trie + symtab. → exit=42. The format is solved.

Stage 3: Extend with `_write` via libSystem. __DATA_CONST
segment, __got section, chain fixups with one bind entry,
__stubs in __TEXT. → "hello" + exit=42. Full import path
validated, but each stage took ~10 round trips to the Mac.

STAGE 4 AND THE SHORTCUT

Before writing the 400-line emitter rewrite, one last probe:
what if we just put raw `svc #0x80` for write and exit, in a
binary that has libSystem in its LC_LOAD_DYLIB but never calls
into it?

→ "hello" + exit=42.

Apple Silicon allows raw BSD syscalls from user mode, as long
as the binary has libSystem in its load graph. It does not have
to call libSystem — dyld just has to see it referenced. This is
not documented. It is almost certainly an implementation detail.

What would have been a 400-line emitter with GOT, stubs, chain
fixups, import tracking, codegen swap to `bl __stub_N` collapsed
to ~200 lines: match the Stage 2 probe layout and translate
syscall numbers from Linux → BSD in the existing ESYSXLAT chain,
writing to x16 instead of x8, svc #0x80 instead of svc #0.

SHIPPED

v5.3.0 ships with syscall-only programs working on Apple Silicon.
No strings, no globals yet — those want PIE-safe adrp+add/ldr
addressing, which the current aarch64 FIXUP does not emit
(it uses absolute MOVZ/MOVK that breaks under PIE slide).
That is v5.3.1.

LESSONS

  1. Probe-first is the only honest way to work against a kernel
     that will not tell you why it killed your process. Build
     standalone programs that produce the target byte stream.
     Iterate at the byte level, not at the compiler level.

  2. Get ground truth from the platform's own tooling. Clang's
     output on the target machine is the spec. The docs are not.

  3. Ask questions the kernel is forced to answer. "Does raw SVC
     work?" cannot be answered by reading Apple's source. It can
     be answered by a 40-line Mach-O builder and a single exec.

  4. Expect every kernel decision to be implementation-defined
     until proven otherwise. The libSystem-in-load-graph rule
     is almost certainly not guaranteed forever. If it breaks
     in a future macOS, we fall back to the full stub/GOT path
     — which is why `src/backend/macho/imports.cyr` is staged
     in v5.3.0 even though nothing calls it yet.

  5. Ship the narrow scope honestly. "Apple Silicon syscall-only"
     is real working hardware support and a defensible roadmap
     entry. Waiting for full feature parity before shipping
     anything would have delayed Apple Silicon for months.

TIME

Three focused sessions, roughly a full working day total:

  Session 1: Stages 1 through 3 (~5 hours)
  Session 2: Raw SVC probe + emitter rewrite + closeout (~4 hours)

For context: every previous Cyrius target (Linux x86_64,
Linux aarch64, macOS x86_64, cyrius-x bytecode) took longer.
The probe-first methodology paid for itself on its first use
against a hostile platform.

                                                      — 2026-04-18

[[entries]]
name = "v5_4_x_gotchas_bundle"
description = "Bundled field notes from the v5.4.x release arc — things that surprised future-me during debugging"
category = "compiler"
---
Consolidated gotchas from the v5.4.x release arc. Each cost a
debug cycle; recording so future-me / other agents don't re-
discover them.

=== SYNTAX / TYPE SYSTEM ===

1. `var name[N]` allocates N BYTES, not N elements.
   Setting `var state[25]` for a 25-lane u64 Keccak buffer gave
   25 bytes (should have been 200). SIGSEGV on first absorb.
   Fix: use element-count × 8 explicitly — `var state[200]`.
   (v5.4.15 keccak, project_v5413_keccak.md)

2. `^` binds TIGHTER than binary `-`.
   `T1 ^ 0 - 1` parses as `(T1 ^ 0) - 1 = T1 - 1`, NOT
   `T1 ^ -1` (which would be bitwise NOT). Always use an
   explicit `-1` literal: `T1 ^ -1`. Cyrius supports negative
   literals since v4.x.
   (v5.4.15 keccak chi step — wrong NIST output byte pattern)

3. Cyrius's `>>` on 64-bit ints is LOGICAL shift, not
   arithmetic. Probe: `0x8000000000000001 >> 63 == 1`, not -1.
   Naive rotl `(x << n) | (x >> (64-n))` works without mask.
   Caveat: lib/u128.cyr's `_u128_lshr64` has an obsolete
   comment suggesting arithmetic-shift semantics — the comment
   is wrong; the code path is defensive belt-and-suspenders.
   (v5.4.15 keccak rotl + v5.4.19 regallim inline)

4. `var` CANNOT be redeclared in the same scope, even across
   elif/else branches. Cyrius treats `if/elif/else` bodies as
   one scope for `var` purposes.
       if (x) { var buf[8]; ... }
       elif (y) { var buf[16]; ... }  # ERROR: redeclaration
   Workaround: rename (`buf_a`, `buf_b`), pull the decl above
   the if, or use a bare `{ }` scope.
   (v5.4.17 lib/toml.cyr multi-line fix — collision between
   the array-scan and unquoted-value branches)

5. `str_data(s)` returns a pointer to the Str's backing
   buffer, which is NOT NUL-terminated. `streq(str_data(s),
   "literal")` walks off the end and compares garbage.
   Correct form: `str_eq_cstr(s, "literal")` or go via
   `toml_get(pairs, "literal")` which encapsulates this.
   (v5.4.17 toml test writing — false-negative assertions)

=== PREPROCESSOR ===

6. Undefined-function calls were SOFT warnings until v5.4.19.
   A typo like `bench_print_all` (should be `bench_report_all`)
   compiled with just `warning: undefined function ...` and
   produced a broken binary that hung at runtime. v5.4.19
   added `cc5 --strict` which hard-fails. ENABLE IT IN CI.
   (v5.4.15 keccak bench → v5.4.19 --strict)

7. `#ifplat` directive (v5.4.19) is sugar for `#ifdef
   CYRIUS_ARCH_<UPPER>` — fully-separate detectors (ISIFPLAT,
   ISENDPLAT) with its own `PP_IFPLAT_MATCH` evaluator that
   hashes the platform token to the canonical CYRIUS_ARCH_*
   symbol. Supports x86 / aarch64. Unknown tokens fail closed.
   Semantically identical to #ifdef; the two forms coexist and
   nest cleanly.

8. `ISIF` (for `#if`) explicitly rejects byte-4 == 'd' (to
   avoid matching `#ifdef`) but not 'p'. `#ifplat` passes
   ISIF's first 3 bytes (`# i f`) but fails its byte-3-
   must-be-space check, so no collision. Nevertheless, when
   adding new `#ifX` directives, check ISIF's rejection list
   and add your initial char.

=== AARCH64 CROSS-COMPILE ===

9. After editing `src/frontend/lex.cyr`, REBUILD BOTH
   `build/cc5` AND `build/cc5_aarch64` before running tests.
   The committed cross-compiler gets stale quickly and
   produces confusing test failures. Pulsar handles it;
   manual workflows must remember.

10. Shared `src/cc/parse.cyr` has raw x86-emit paths (E2 /
    EB byte sequences) that should be arch-guarded when run
    under the aarch64 backend. Known site: parse.cyr:277
    `E2(S, 0xB848)` (x86 REX + `mov rax, imm64` prefix).
    v5.4.19's EW alignment assert in aarch64/emit.cyr CATCHES
    THIS DYNAMICALLY — if a shared parse.cyr path leaks x86
    bytes into the aarch64 stream, the next EW call hard-fails
    with a clear message. Static source audit deferred to
    v5.5.x once the assert has had time to catch real ones.
    (feedback_unguarded_x86_emit memory)

=== CALLING CONVENTION ===

11. Cyrius's aarch64 calling convention uses x0..x5 + stack
    (mirrors x86_64 SysV), NOT AAPCS64's x0..x7. Args 7+ get
    pushed via `str xN, [sp, #-16]!` (16-byte slots for SP
    alignment). `fncall7` / `fncall8` in lib/fnptr.cyr follow
    this — they are cyrius-to-cyrius safe but NOT AAPCS64-
    compatible for args 7-8. Direct calls to C functions with
    7+ args on aarch64 need a C shim.
    (v5.4.13 fncall ceiling work, project_v5412_render_pass.md)

12. Struct-by-value arguments are NEVER safe for direct
    `fncallN`. SysV §3.2.3 / AAPCS64 §B.4 aggregate rules
    split them across regs or stack-home; fncallN only loads
    integer registers. Mabda's wgpu-native crashes were all
    struct-by-value, never a fncall6 bug per se. Always shim.
    (v5.4.13 docs/ffi/struct-packing.md)

=== RUNTIME ===

13. `lib/thread.cyr`'s post-clone(CLONE_VM) child trampoline
    is INLINE ASM because plain Cyrius code would read locals
    via parent's inherited RBP and stomp parent's stack. Both
    x86 (v5.4.10) and aarch64 (v5.4.11) use the trampoline.
    If you touch thread.cyr, respect: child never touches
    RBP/x29 after syscall; only RSP/sp + RAX/x0. Post-syscall
    test rax/x0; jnz/cbnz to parent path.

14. thread_join uses shared (not private) futex wait to
    match kernel's CLONE_CHILD_CLEARTID wake semantic. Don't
    add FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG — the kernel's wake side doesn't
    use it; private wait would never unblock.
    (v5.4.10 majra cbarrier_arrive_and_wait crash fix)

15. `include "lib/*"` boundary + inline asm with large
    disp32-memop block + caller-supplied output pointer =
    stores silently no-op at runtime. Minimal repros don't
    fire; sigil's 120-byte 14-round AES-256 block does.
    Byte-identical objdump either way. Root cause open
    (v5.5.x pillar 8, feedback_inline_asm_include_bug.md).
    Sigil 2.9.0 works around by pinning `aes_ni_available()`
    to 0 and staying on software AES-GCM.

=== RELEASE MACHINERY ===

16. Pre-v5.4.18: six places hardcoded the toolchain binary
    list (release.yml ×2, install.sh ×3, pulsar.cyr ×1).
    Adding a tool required six synchronized edits; missing
    one silently dropped the tool from a codepath.
    v5.4.18 collapsed all six into `[release]` table in
    cyrius.cyml.

17. Pre-v5.4.12: `~/.cyrius/versions/<v>/lib/` and `bin/`
    were created at install time and NEVER auto-updated.
    `cyrius.cyml` dep bumps reached the repo but not the
    install snapshot. New downstream projects got stale deps
    until reinstall. v5.4.18 added `install.sh --refresh-only`
    called from `version-bump.sh` post-bump hook. Every
    version bump now reconciles the snapshot automatically.

18. `scripts/release-lib.sh` pre-v5.4.12-1 had its own
    parallel list of dep tags that silently drifted from
    cyrius.cyml. Three dep bumps shipped in tarballs with
    stale content (sigil 2.8.3 instead of 2.8.4 at v5.4.12).
    Fixed by making release-lib.sh parse cyrius.cyml directly
    via awk over `[deps.NAME]` blocks.

=== TEST HARNESS ===

19. `stderr leaks into stdout` during test compilation when
    the compiler emits warning/note text and the test harness
    captures stdout as the output binary. Always redirect
    stderr separately: `cat test.cyr | build/cc5 2>/tmp/err
    > /tmp/bin`. Otherwise the binary starts with human-
    readable noise and SIGSEGVs when the ELF loader can't
    parse it.

20. `lib/syscalls_x86_64_linux.cyr` references `alloc`
    without including alloc.cyr. Standalone `include
    "lib/syscalls.cyr"` consumers get the undefined-function
    warning for alloc (and crash at runtime if the affected
    fns are reached). Pre-existing; deferred to v5.5.x
    cleanup. Workaround: include alloc.cyr whenever you
    include syscalls.cyr.

=== META ===

21. Self-host byte-identical proves cc5 is a FIXED POINT,
    not that cc5 is CORRECT. A bug in compilation of other
    programs (not cc5 itself) passes self-host verify. Always
    run the full test suite (`sh scripts/check.sh`) after any
    lex / parse / emit change. v5.4.19's lib-call-site
    migration attempt had self-host green but thread tests
    0/6 red — self-host was a lie for that scope.

[[entries]]
name = "windows_arc_anticipated_gotchas"
description = "Pre-flight gotcha bundle for v5.5.3 (Win64 ABI) + v5.5.4 (native self-host) + v5.5.5+ (PE tail). Record before we hit them, not after."
category = "compiler"
---
Things that WILL bite during the v5.5.x Windows-dominated arc.
Surfaced from the MS x64 ABI spec, the PE/COFF PE32+ spec,
Agner Fog's calling-convention notes, and Chris Wellons'
libchkstk notes. Recorded BEFORE debugging so future-claude
hitting a symptom can jump straight to cause.

=== ABI / CALLING CONVENTION ===

1. RSP ALIGNMENT AT CALL IS NON-NEGOTIABLE.
   Win64 requires RSP ≡ 0 (mod 16) at every `call` instruction.
   Entry to a fn has RSP ≡ 8 (mod 16) because `call` just pushed
   an 8-byte return addr onto a 16-aligned stack. EFNPRO's
   `push rbp` restores RSP ≡ 0. `sub rsp, N` for shadow + locals
   must keep N a multiple of 16. EEXIT uses `sub rsp, 0x28` (40 B)
   — 32 shadow + 8 pad = 40, and 40 + 8 (return addr) = 48 which
   IS a multiple of 16. The 8-byte pad is not accidental. If you
   write `sub rsp, 0x20` (32 B shadow, no pad), your CALL lands
   on misaligned RSP and the callee's SSE ops fault.

2. SHADOW SPACE IS ALWAYS 32 BYTES. EVEN FOR ZERO-ARG CALLS.
   Zero-arg `call` still needs `sub rsp, 0x20` (+ 8 pad) before
   it. The 32 B area is OWNED by the callee — it may spill
   RCX/RDX/R8/R9 there regardless of how many args it took. The
   caller cannot save data there across the call.

3. FIRST-FOUR-ARGS REGISTER SLOT IS "OWNED" BY CALLEE.
   A callee that takes 2 args can still write to the R8 and R9
   home slots in its shadow area. Unused arg slots are NOT free
   scratch for the caller — they belong to the called function.

4. CALLEE-SAVE FLIP IS ALMOST FREE FOR CYRIUS.
   Win64 adds RDI, RSI to the callee-saved set. Cyrius's codegen
   doesn't USE RDI/RSI inside function bodies (only as arg-pass
   registers at the boundary, where they're immediately spilled
   to local slots). So EFNPRO/EFNEPI don't need extra push/pop.
   XMM6-XMM15 callee-save likewise no-op: we emit no SSE today.

5. RED ZONE DOES NOT EXIST ON WIN64.
   SysV has 128 bytes below RSP that's safe from signal handlers.
   Win64 has ZERO. Any byte below RSP may be clobbered by an
   async callback or a debugger. `mov [rsp-8], rax` then CALL is
   a WIN64 BUG even though it works on Linux. Cyrius doesn't use
   the red zone today (no compiled code writes below RSP), but
   if any optimization pass is ported from SysV-assuming code,
   check for red-zone assumptions.

6. STRUCT-RETURN-BY-VALUE SHIFTS ALL OTHER ARGS.
   A fn returning a 24-byte struct has a HIDDEN pointer arg in
   RCX. What looks like the first user arg actually goes in RDX.
   Silently corrupts if ESTOREPARM pidx mapping isn't aware of
   the return-size threshold. The SysV convention is the same
   shape BUT uses RDI — easy to over-generalize.

7. VARIADIC FLOAT DUPLICATION — PRINTF'S QUIET KILLER.
   `printf("%f", 3.14)` must load 3.14 into BOTH XMM1 AND RDX
   because varargs has no prototype telling the caller which to
   use. Forget this and printf prints garbage for floats but
   correct for ints. Cyrius has no varargs today; if we add
   them (pulsar log formatting, assert macros), this must go in
   FIRST — debugging after the fact is brutal because the int
   path works.

8. LINUX `0F 05` SYSCALL BYTES IN A PE IS AN ABI LEAK.
   v5.4.4's CI gate (`xxd -p hello.exe | grep 0f05` asserts
   empty) catches any codegen path that forgets the _TARGET_PE
   guard. If v5.5.3's fncall migration adds a new emit path,
   keep this gate — it'll catch any fallthrough-to-Linux bug.

=== WINDOWS I/O / SELF-HOST ===

9. POWERSHELL `>` REDIRECTION CORRUPTS BINARY OUTPUT.
   PowerShell's stdout capture reads as text and re-encodes.
   PowerShell 5.1 emits UTF-16 LE with BOM. PowerShell 7+ emits
   UTF-8 with BOM (or no BOM depending on preference vars).
   Either way, piping PE bytes through `|` or `>` mangles them.
   SYMPTOM: `cc5_win.exe < src > out.exe` produces an invalid
   PE that Windows rejects ("not a valid Win32 application").
   FIXES (either works):
     cmd  /c "cc5_win.exe < src > out.exe"
     pwsh: Start-Process cc5_win.exe -RedirectStandardInput src \
                                     -RedirectStandardOutput out.exe \
                                     -Wait -NoNewWindow
   In GitHub Actions, prefer `shell: cmd` for the pipe step.
   `shell: pwsh` is fine for anything not involving binary I/O.

10. GETSTDHANDLE CONSTANTS ARE UNSIGNED DWORDS.
    Microsoft docs define STD_INPUT_HANDLE as `((DWORD)-10)`.
    In a language that doesn't parse C headers, the ACTUAL value
    is 0xFFFFFFF6 (= 4294967286). Our PE reroute passes this in
    RCX (first arg to GetStdHandle). Passing -10 as signed 64-bit
    = 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF6 is NOT the same thing — the upper 32
    bits must be zero. Use `mov ecx, 0xFFFFFFF6` (zero-extends)
    not `mov rcx, -10` (sign-extends).
    Values: STDIN=-10=0xFFFFFFF6, STDOUT=-11=0xFFFFFFF5,
            STDERR=-12=0xFFFFFFF4.

11. CREATEFILEW WANTS UTF-16 PATHS.
    LPCWSTR = wide char. `path.c_str()` won't work — we need
    to widen "lib/foo.cyr" to L"lib\\0f\\0o\\0o\\0.\\0c\\0y\\0r\\0"
    (naive ASCII-to-UTF-16 is just zero-interleave, works for
    pure ASCII paths).
    If v5.5.1's sys_open reroute emits narrow paths (ASCII
    byte stream), CreateFileW will interpret them as UTF-16
    and read garbage character codes. Audit the reroute during
    v5.5.4 planning; if it assumes ASCII, split into a v5.5.4b
    sub-item. CreateFileA exists but is deprecated for new code;
    using CreateFileW + zero-interleave widening is cleaner than
    calling MultiByteToWideChar.

12. CRLF TRANSLATION IS A CRT FEATURE, NOT A WIN32 ONE.
    ReadFile/WriteFile are BYTE-EXACT. The CRLF auto-translation
    (0x0D 0x0A ↔ 0x0A) that breaks binary file I/O on DOS and
    old Windows code happens in `fopen(..., "rt")`'s text-mode
    CRT layer. We're not linking CRT. Our ReadFile returns raw
    bytes; our WriteFile writes raw bytes. No translation.

13. FILE_ATTRIBUTE_NORMAL IS 0x80. Zero is NOT a valid attribute.
    If the sys_open reroute passes `mode = 0` (as on Linux, where
    `mode` is the permission bits and 0 works for read-only), it
    will produce a confusing-but-accepted call on Windows. The
    correct Win32 default for dwFlagsAndAttributes is 0x80.

14. INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE IS -1, NOT NULL.
    CreateFileW returns -1 (0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF) on failure, not 0.
    Matching on `handle == 0` as failure check misses this.
    GetStdHandle additionally can return NULL (if the process
    has no associated standard handles); that's a separate "no
    stdio" state, not an error. Check for both.

=== PE / RELOC / CHKSTK ===

15. .RELOC BLOCK SIZE INCLUDES THE 8-BYTE HEADER.
    `BlockSize = 8 + (entries * 2) + padding`. Forgetting the
    +8 produces a .reloc that the loader walks past its own end.
    Relocs MUST be DWORD-aligned; odd entry counts need a final
    IMAGE_REL_BASED_ABSOLUTE (type 0, value 0x0000) pad entry.

16. IMAGE_FILE_RELOCS_STRIPPED + DYNAMIC_BASE ARE MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE.
    Setting both tells the loader "I have no relocs, but please
    relocate me anyway." The loader honors RELOCS_STRIPPED and
    silently ignores DYNAMIC_BASE. No ASLR, no error. If you
    ship .reloc, clear RELOCS_STRIPPED first.

17. __CHKSTK IS THE COMPILER'S RESPONSIBILITY.
    Unlike SysV Linux where the kernel grows the stack on any
    access-fault, Win64 requires the compiler to emit a probe
    for any frame ≥ 4 KB. Skipping it doesn't fail immediately
    — small inputs still work — but a deep recursion or a big
    local array silently skips the guard page and the kernel
    delivers STATUS_STACK_OVERFLOW without an unwind opportunity.
    Cyrius is safe today (all frames < 4 KB); if that changes,
    36 bytes of inline asm implements __chkstk per Wellons.

18. DEBUGGER STACK-WALK WILL BREAK AT NON-LEAF CYRIUS FNS.
    Without .pdata/.xdata, Windows' unwind API (RtlVirtualUnwind
    etc.) can't walk past a Cyrius stack frame. Consequence:
    WinDbg / VS debugger show "??? ???" above the first cyrius
    frame in the call stack. Stepping works; `k` command doesn't.
    Acceptable for now; if we grow Windows dev ergonomics (e.g.
    debugging a mabda Windows port), revisit.

=== CI / WINDOWS-LATEST ===

19. windows-latest IS GITHUB-HOSTED, NOT SELF-HOSTED.
    The existing ci.yml windows-native job uses the public runner.
    No installation steps needed; PE .exe runs directly. Costs
    ~10× Linux runner minutes per job; keep the matrix tight.
    Self-hosted Windows runners exist but add provisioning cost
    we don't need yet.

20. fc /b IS WINDOWS' CMP.
    For byte-identical assertion on Windows, use `fc /b a.exe
    b.exe` in cmd, or `Compare-Object ... -SyncWindow 0` in
    pwsh (slower, buffers the whole file). For CI, `fc /b`
    exits with `FC: no differences encountered` and exit code 0
    on match, non-zero otherwise.

21. POWERSHELL Start-Process DOES NOT ENCODE.
    Despite PowerShell's text-mangling reputation, Start-Process
    with -RedirectStandardOutput writes the child's raw bytes
    directly to the file. That's why the existing windows-native
    job can assert stdout contents — it's a real byte stream,
    not a re-encoded one. This is the safe way to capture
    binary-ish output from a child process in pwsh.

[[entries]]
name = "v5_5_x_platform_rounding_gotchas"
description = "v5.5.x Mach-O libSystem + Windows native self-host gotchas — things that burned hours and shouldn't burn hours again"
category = "compiler"
---
v5.5.x rounded out the non-Linux platform support started in
v5.3.x / v5.4.x. Most of the release cost wasn't writing the emission
code — it was learning where the platforms lied about what they
wanted. Capturing those here so future Mach-O or PE work in v5.6.x+
doesn't rediscover them.

=== MACH-O / APPLE SILICON ===

1. CODESIGN'S "OBJECT FILE FORMAT UNRECOGNIZED" IS DIAGNOSTICALLY USELESS.
   When `codesign -s - --force` rejects a Mach-O with
   `the file is object file format unrecognized, invalid, or
   unsuitable`, the error points at LITERALLY NOTHING. Could be
   byte zero or byte 33000. Happened during v5.5.11 probe
   iteration with LC_DYLD_CHAINED_FIXUPS — pointer_format=2
   (DYLD_CHAINED_PTR_64) and pointer_format=6
   (DYLD_CHAINED_PTR_64_OFFSET) both fail the same way. Chain
   header bytes looked right, import table matched Apple's doc,
   __got entry encoded per spec. Codesign didn't care.

   Don't debug chained fixups byte-by-byte when hitting this
   message. Pivot to classic binds (LC_DYLD_INFO_ONLY) — it's
   macOS 10.9+ compatible and codesign accepts it without
   complaint. Chained fixups require macOS 12+ AND the binary to
   match an extremely strict shape that codesign validates but
   doesn't describe.

   v5.5.11 probe succeeded on classic binds first try after the
   pivot; v5.5.12 landed the same path into EMITMACHO_ARM64.

2. MH_NOUNDEFS CANNOT COEXIST WITH REAL UNDEF SYMBOLS.
   The old v5.3.x Mach-O arm64 emitter set MH_NOUNDEFS (0x1) in
   the mach_header flags. That's fine when your binary uses raw
   `svc #0x80` for all syscalls (no libSystem imports, no undef
   symbols). As soon as you add a real undef like `_exit`, the
   loader rejects the binary. v5.5.12 flipped flags from
   0x00200085 to 0x00200084.

   Easy to miss in review — mach_header flags are a 32-bit
   bitfield with meaningless display in most tools. If you add
   an undef, drop NOUNDEFS.

3. adrp IMMEDIATE ENCODING IS NOT "BITS 30-5 OF THE 21-BIT IMM".
   The ARM ARM describes adrp as:
       op=1 | immlo(2 bits) | 10000 | immhi(19 bits) | rd(5 bits)
   Where imm21 = (immhi << 2) | immlo. The low 2 bits of the
   encoded imm live at bits 30-29 of the instruction word; the
   high 19 bits live at bits 23-5. This is NOT a linear
   "shift imm into bit 5 and mask".

   For `adrp x16, #4 pages`:
     imm21 = 4 = 0b100 → immhi=1, immlo=0
     Word: 0x90000030 (NOT 0x90000050, which is imm=8)

   The v5.5.11 probe initially used 0x90000050 and would have
   loaded from __LINKEDIT instead of __DATA_CONST.

   Recipe for any future `adrp xN, #imm21`:
     immhi = imm21 >> 2
     immlo = imm21 & 3
     word = 0x90000000 | (immlo << 29) | (immhi << 5) | rd

4. SEGMENT INDEX IN BIND OPCODES IS LC_SEGMENT_64 ORDER, NOT
   LOAD-SEGMENT ORDER.
   `SET_SEGMENT_AND_OFFSET_ULEB` opcode (high nibble 0x70) takes
   a segment index in the low nibble. The index counts all
   LC_SEGMENT_64 load commands in emission order, INCLUDING
   __PAGEZERO (which has no file backing):
     __PAGEZERO = 0, __TEXT = 1, __DATA_CONST = 2,
     __DATA = 3 (if present), __LINKEDIT = 3 or 4

   For binding into __DATA_CONST the opcode byte is always 0x72
   (0x70 | 2). Index stable across has_data/no_data layouts
   because __DATA slides in AFTER __DATA_CONST.

5. BUILD_VERSION MINOS CANNOT BE BELOW THE PLATFORM FLOOR.
   Apple Silicon ARM64 macOS starts at 11.0 (Big Sur). Setting
   minos=10.9 on an arm64 binary gets the loader to refuse with
   "executable is requesting to be run on a platform below its
   minimum supported version". Tempted to set 10.9 for classic-bind
   support — don't. Use minos=11.0 for arm64, 10.9 for x86_64.

6. `DYLD_PRINT_APIS=1` IS THE BEST DEBUGGING TOOL WE DIDN'T
   LEARN ABOUT IN TIME.
   When a Mach-O fails to load, setting `DYLD_PRINT_APIS=1`
   before running emits every dyld API call (mapping segments,
   walking binds, resolving imports) to stderr. Far more useful
   than codesign's opaque errors. Also:
     DYLD_PRINT_BINDINGS=1 — what got bound where
     DYLD_PRINT_SEGMENTS=1 — segment load map

=== WINDOWS / PE NATIVE SELF-HOST ===

7. `/proc/self/*` HAS NO WINDOWS EQUIVALENT.
   v5.5.9 burned three rounds finding three separate `/proc/self/*`
   readbacks that had to be gated behind `#ifdef CYRIUS_TARGET_LINUX`:
     - main_win.cyr `--version`/`--strict` cmdline parse
       (`/proc/self/cmdline`)
     - lex.cyr `_init_cyrius_lib()` HOME env read
       (`/proc/self/environ`)
     - fixup.cyr `_read_env()` env-var scan
       (`/proc/self/environ`)
   Each crashed cc5_win.exe silently. Breadcrumb probe
   methodology (syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2, "Bn", ...) before each
   suspect block, narrowed by bisection) found them in one SSH
   round-trip per breadcrumb.

   Audit rule: anywhere cc5 opens a path starting with `/proc/`,
   `/sys/`, or `/dev/`, that code needs a `CYRIUS_TARGET_LINUX`
   guard or a cross-platform equivalent.

8. WRITEFILE RETURNS BOOL IN RAX, NOT BYTES-WRITTEN.
   v5.5.10 was a 5-byte fix because EWRITE_PE didn't read the
   `lpNumberOfBytesWritten` out-parameter at `[rsp+0x28]` before
   unwinding. It returned WriteFile's BOOL success flag (1) in
   rax. The caller's write loop did `written += w` with w=1
   each iteration, so for olen=1536 it wrote olen + (olen-1) +
   ... + 1 = olen*(olen+1)/2 = 1,180,416 B total.

   The triangular growth pattern is the tell: if file size is
   N*(N+1)/2 where N is the intended size, you have a 1-byte
   bool masquerading as a byte count.

   Audit rule: EVERY Win32 API reroute calling an API with an
   `lpSomethingCount` out-parameter needs a `mov rax, [rsp+offset]`
   post-call to propagate the real count. The other reroutes
   (ReadFile, CreateFileW, CloseHandle, SetFilePointerEx,
   VirtualAlloc) should be audited against this rule on next
   review.

9. WINDOWS HAS NO `brk`.
   main_win.cyr v5.5.7 initialized the heap with
   `syscall(SYS_BRK, ...)`. PE backend didn't reroute SYS_BRK
   (12). The syscall fell through to the Linux encoding and
   crashed with STATUS_ACCESS_VIOLATION before main_win even
   started. v5.5.8 swapped to `syscall(SYS_MMAP, 0, 32MB, 3,
   0x22, -1, 0)` which works on Linux (honest mmap) and Windows
   (routes to VirtualAlloc, ignores prot/flags).

   Rule: prefer SYS_MMAP over SYS_BRK in any code path that may
   run on non-Linux.

=== CROSS-CUTTING ===

10. PIN LIMITATIONS TO NUMBERS, DON'T DOCUMENT THEM AS "FUTURE
    WORK".
    v5.5.4 skipped shadow-space for cyrius-to-cyrius calls and
    noted it as "documented limitation — C FFI via fnptr
    requires a shim". Two patches later (v5.5.7) we went back
    and lifted strict shadow-space compliance retroactively
    because leaving it documented didn't actually leave the
    decision stable — it kept drifting into other patches.

    Rule: when tempted to write "documented limitation" or
    "future work" or "shim required", instead pin a patch
    number. "Closed in v5.5.7" is clean; "documented limitation
    since v5.5.4" rots. Formal discipline captured in memory as
    `feedback_pin_not_document.md`.

[[entries]]
name = "v5_5_26_27_gotchas_bundle"
description = "Landmines from v5.5.26 / v5.5.26-1 / v5.5.27 — reserved keywords, distlib verify, substring-match, cyrius-test dep order, bench no-args"
category = "cyrius_compiler"
---
Five gotchas surfaced while landing the NSS identity arc (v5.5.26
pwd/grp, v5.5.27 shadow/pam) and the patra distlib migration:

=== 1. Reserved keywords should NOT say "got unknown" ===

Before v5.5.26 the error for `var match = 1;` was:
  error: expected identifier, got match
For `var in = 1;` / `var default` / `var shared` it was worse:
  error: expected identifier, got unknown
because TOKNAME didn't have cases for tokens 59/76/78.

Fix: TOKNAME in src/common/util.cyr gained the missing keyword
cases (23 else, 58 case, 59 default, 76 in, 78 shared, 79 object),
a new IS_KEYWORD_TOK(typ) helper lists every keyword token type,
and ERR_EXPECT branches on "expected identifier + got keyword":

  error: expected identifier, got reserved keyword 'match'
         (cannot be used as an identifier;
          rename the variable/field/fn)

Same-kind bugs elsewhere usually betray an enum-driven dispatch
that forgot to add an entry. Grep for `"unknown"` in TOKNAME-like
tables and ask whether every code path that produces the value
has a label.

=== 2. Substring matches on config keys need boundary checks ===

`cbt/deps.cyr`'s Phase 1 matched "stdlib" anywhere in the
manifest via a bare `memeq("stdlib", 6)`. Patra 1.5.5's cyrius.cyml
had a comment containing "stdlib prerequisites"; the matcher
caught the comment, then `_parse_toml_str_array` grabbed the
next array (patra's `[lib] modules = ["src/file.cyr", ...]`),
and each path was resolved as `/home/runner/.cyrius/lib/src/file.cyr.cyr`.
Patra CI broke on every release attempt.

Fix (v5.5.26-1): before accepting the match, require the preceding
byte to be a non-identifier char (not 0-9, A-Z, a-z, _) AND the
line must not be a comment (no `#` before the key on the same
line). 30 lines in cbt/deps.cyr.

Lesson: if you're scanning for a keyword in user-facing config,
check boundaries on BOTH sides. Post-byte check alone (requiring
` ` or `=` after the keyword) is not enough — the preceding
context matters too.

=== 3. `cyrius distlib` verify step cannot assume standalone compile ===

v5.5.26 added a compile-check on the generated bundle and exited
1 on unresolved symbols. That broke patra 1.5.5's release CI:
consumer-bundles (patra/yukti/mabda/sankoch) are DESIGNED to be
concatenated into a consumer's compile unit that already has
stdlib in scope. A standalone compile WILL fail — that's expected,
not a defect.

Fix (v5.5.27): soften verify to an info message via new `_info`
helper in cbt/core.cyr. Bundle still gets written; command
returns 0; users get an advisory note if the bundle has unresolved
symbols. Same spirit as gofmt/eslint info-vs-error split.

Lesson: verification steps that try to compile half of a compile
unit are usually mis-scoped. Either verify what the consumer
will actually see (requires knowing their stdlib context), or
don't verify — don't half-verify and fail on expected-unresolved.

=== 4. `cyrius test` auto-prepends deps BEFORE the test's own stdlib includes ===

PRE-EXISTING, known since v5.5.26. `cyrius test` builds a compile
unit that looks like:

  include "lib/sakshi.cyr"   (auto-prepended from deps)
  include "lib/patra.cyr"    (auto-prepended; transitively uses SYS_LSEEK)
  ...
  # test file:
  include "lib/syscalls.cyr" (defines SYS_LSEEK — too late)
  ...

Result: any test whose deps reference stdlib fails to compile via
`cyrius test` harness, with errors like:
  error:lib/patra.cyr:85: undefined variable 'SYS_LSEEK'
  error:lib/freelist.cyr:67: undefined variable 'PROT_READ'

Workaround: every check.sh gate uses direct `build/cc5` compile
(not the harness). New tests should follow that pattern until the
harness is fixed (tracked, no fixed slot yet — fix = reorder
auto-prepend so stdlib comes first, or make each dep bundle
declare its stdlib prereqs that distlib hoists).

Don't mistake this harness issue for a code bug in the test —
run the test directly via `cat test.tcyr | build/cc5 > /tmp/bin && /tmp/bin`
as the canonical truth.

=== 5. `cyrius bench` no-args should walk, not invoke install-dir scripts ===

Before v5.5.27, `cyrius bench` (no args) invoked
`~/.cyrius/bin/bench-history.sh` — a cyrius-repo-specific CSV
history tracker that makes no sense in a downstream project.
takumi filed the UX gotcha.

Fix (v5.5.27): mirror `cyrius fuzz` / `cyrius test` shape — walk
`benches/*.bcyr` and `tests/bcyr/*.bcyr`, compile and run each.
Cyrius's own CI calls `sh scripts/bench-history.sh` directly, so
unaffected.

Lesson for any future "discover and run" CLI commands: walk the
project's conventional directory; don't reach into the install
dir for behavior the downstream user didn't opt into.

=== Rule of thumb ===

Bundling a release with ecosystem-UX fixes surfaces them early.
v5.5.26 bundled reserved-keyword diag + patra distlib migration;
v5.5.26-1 hotfix caught the substring-match and pwd/grp doc-coverage
regressions; v5.5.27 bundled distlib verify-soften + bench walker.
If shipping new stdlib modules (pwd/grp/shadow/pam), always check
that the related tooling surfaces (cyrdoc, cyrius test harness,
distlib) still play nice. They usually don't — and catching it
in the same patch is cheaper than filing a follow-up.

[[entries]]
name = "v5_5_28_to_40_gotchas_bundle"
description = "Non-obvious gotchas from the v5.5.28 → v5.5.40 stretch of the minor (fdlopen completion, PE Win64 ABI closure, fixup cap raise, parser split, cc3 retirement, closeout)"
category = "cyrius"
---
The tail of v5.5.x (28 → 40) hit a cluster of gotchas that
future-Claude investigations will circle back to. Each one cost
real debug time; recording them so a vidya search hits them
before rediscovery.

=== 1. fdlopen_init_full: PF_* bits and mmap PROT_* bits are NOT 1:1 ===

v5.5.34 fix. ELF program-header flags:
  PF_X = 1
  PF_W = 2
  PF_R = 4

Linux mmap prot flags:
  PROT_READ  = 1
  PROT_WRITE = 2
  PROT_EXEC  = 4

R and X are SWAPPED. Any loader that maps ELF segments into its
own address space (foreign-dlopen, cosmopolitan-pattern, etc.)
must translate — a naïve `prot = p_flags` leaves PF_R-only
segments execute-only. Result: reads from those pages SIGSEGV,
but ld.so's fault handler swallows the SIGSEGV and exits 0
silently. Exit-0-silent is a KILLER symptom to debug — no
observable output.

The v5.5.29 "ld.so enters and exits 0 silent" investigation
spent three attempts on wrong hypotheses (zero-filled auxv,
missing AT_* fields) before the A1 diagnostic (read `base[0]`
post-mmap_elf, before handing to ld.so) localized the SIGSEGV
to mprotect'd segments. 6-line arithmetic swap fixed it.

Kept `programs/fdlopen-phdr-probe.cyr` in-tree as the A1
methodology template: when ld.so goes silent, probe the mapped
pages before handing control off.

=== 2. R11 (not RCX) as __chkstk probe scratch under Win64 ===

v5.5.36 Phase 1 initially emitted the `__chkstk`-equivalent
probe using RCX as the loop iterator. Worked fine for regular
fns. BROKE as soon as v5.5.36 Phase 2b added struct-by-value
return — because Win64 passes the hidden retptr in RCX, and
the probe clobbered it before the callee could stash it.

Fix: use R11 (volatile on both SysV and Win64, NOT an arg
register on either). Same 32-byte probe size, same encoding
length, just a different register choice.

Lesson for any future fn-prologue codegen that uses a scratch
register: PICK FROM THE ABI-VOLATILE, NON-ARG set. R10 and R11
are the safest picks on x86_64 — volatile on both SysV and
Win64, never passed an argument in either ABI.

=== 3. Cross-repo symlink: mabda/lib → cyrius/lib ===

v5.5.34 sidebar. From v5.5.30 through v5.5.33 there was a
recurring mystery: `lib/dynlib.cyr` in the cyrius repo kept
losing the same 111 lines (the dynlib_bootstrap_environ /
_read_auxv / _auxv_get block) between sessions. Four separate
"restore dynlib" commits landed. The pre-commit hook caught
it eventually but couldn't explain why it kept happening.

Root cause: `/home/macro/Repos/mabda/lib` was a symlink to
`/home/macro/Repos/cyrius/lib`. An agent working in mabda that
ran Write or Edit on `lib/<anything>.cyr` wrote through the
symlink into the cyrius repo. mabda-scope agents had no visibility
into cross-repo callers (only cyrius's fdlopen.cyr used those
fns), so dead-code passes removed them on what looked like clean
reasoning. Same 111 lines every time because it was the same
well-reasoned-but-cross-repo-blind decision, re-made.

If you're ever investigating apparently-spontaneous file
corruption in cyrius's lib/, first check for inbound symlinks:

  find /home/macro/Repos -maxdepth 3 -type l -lname "*cyrius/lib*"
  find ~/.cyrius -type l | xargs readlink -f | grep Repos/cyrius

Fix (v5.5.34): retired the mabda symlink; mabda now uses
`cyrius deps` to populate a real `lib/` directory. Added a
Makefile `check-lib-wiring` guard in mabda that fails builds
if lib/ ever becomes a symlink again. cyrius's CLAUDE.md grew
a "Downstream repo setup (ecosystem rule)" section explicitly
forbidding the pattern.

=== 4. Nested-include refactor for byte-identical file splits ===

v5.5.38. Splitting parse.cyr (4971 LOC) and lex.cyr (2355 LOC)
into smaller component files without touching any main_*.cyr
consumer file was done via NESTED INCLUDES:

  # original
  include "src/frontend/parse.cyr"     # 4971 LOC

  # after split
  include "src/frontend/parse.cyr"     # 891 LOC, which itself:
    include "src/frontend/parse_types.cyr"
    include "src/frontend/parse_expr.cyr"
    include "src/frontend/parse_decl.cyr"
    include "src/frontend/parse_ctrl.cyr"
    include "src/frontend/parse_fn.cyr"

Because cyrius's `include` is textual inlining and preserves
line-order, the flattened fn-definition sequence is IDENTICAL
to the pre-split file. Self-host byte-identical by construction,
and verified at each of six extraction stages via
`cmp /tmp/cc5_new build/cc5-from-before-stage`. Not just
gen1 == gen2 self-host — provable zero-delta mechanical move.

Future refactor pattern: extract, update parse.cyr's include
line list, verify cmp-clean, move to next extraction. Don't
bundle multiple extractions per verify step — bisecting a
break then requires more work than just linear-stepping.

=== 5. cyrius self had been silently failing since v5.0.0 ===

v5.5.39 retirement of the cc3-era `src/cc/` + entry point files
uncovered a long-standing bug in `cbt/commands.cyr` `cmd_self`:
it was piping `src/compiler.cyr` (the old cc3 entry point)
through cc5 for the self-host check. `src/compiler.cyr` had
been broken since v5.1.9's partial cleanup — its `include`
list referenced `src/cc/util.cyr`, `src/cc/jump.cyr`, and
`src/cc/fixup.cyr` which no longer existed on disk. Build
output was garbage (undefined-fn warnings for every helper),
and `cyrius self` reported `FAIL: cc5!=cc5` on every run.

Nobody noticed because:
  - bootstrap/CI/scripts don't invoke `cyrius self`
  - the proper self-host check lives in scripts/check.sh
    (uses src/main.cyr, which works)
  - the cbt CLI was rarely exercised for self

Fix: one-character-ish change — repointed cmd_self at
src/main.cyr. `cyrius self` now reports truth.

Lesson: if a tool subcommand has been "passing" forever without
anyone checking, be suspicious. Especially self-host / correctness
checks. They should fail LOUDLY when broken, not silently PASS
on vacuous input.

=== 6. tests/heapmap.sh regex: 2+ spaces required, dropped 7+ hex digits ===

v5.5.40 closeout. The heap-auditor's regex `^#   0x[0-9A-Fa-f]+  +[a-zA-Z_]`
required 2+ spaces between the hex offset and the region name.
Column-aligned comments have different spacing depending on
hex-digit count:

  #   0x00000  input_buf     [...]    # 5-digit offset + 2 spaces
  #   0x11A000 var_noffs     [...]    # 6-digit offset + 1 space
  #   0x150B000 fixup_tbl    [...]    # 7-digit offset + 1 space

Regex matched the 5-digit line (2 spaces) and silently skipped
the 6/7-digit lines (1 space). Net effect: every region past
0xFC000 was INVISIBLE to the auditor. That includes the IR
region (0xECA000+), the codebuf/output buffers, token arrays,
and the v5.5.37 relocated fixup_tbl at 0x150B000.

Audits reported "47 regions, 0 warnings" when the real count
was 72. The v5.5.37 fixup_tbl relocation went unchecked by
the tooling for three patches.

Fix (v5.5.40 closeout): relax regex from `  +` to ` +`. Now
72 regions, 0 overlaps (genuine).

Lesson: CI/audit tooling silently skipping work is WORSE than
failing loudly. If a regex-based parser could plausibly miss
a line format, audit the output count against the known region
count. One trivial assertion would have caught this years ago.

=== Bundle rule of thumb ===

This v5.5.28–v5.5.40 stretch shipped ~12 patches across
substantive platform work (fdlopen completion, Win64 ABI,
fixup cap raise, parser split, cc3 retirement, closeout). Most
of the hard-to-debug issues came from SUBTLE INTERACTIONS:
R11 vs RCX under two different ABIs; ELF PF bits vs mmap
PROT bits; regex whitespace vs column alignment; cross-repo
symlink vs cross-repo dead-code analysis.

For any future minor with similar platform-arc work, the
highest-ROI investment is the DIAGNOSTIC probe (fdlopen-phdr-probe.cyr
pattern) — write a tiny program that reads the state the
real code produces, surface it before the next opaque failure
mode fires. When the symptom is "exit 0 silent" or "byte-
identical but wrong," diagnostics > re-reasoning.

[[entries]]
name = "v5_6_x_optimization_arc_gotchas_bundle"
description = "v5.6.0 — v5.6.17 gotchas: IR-pass debugging methodology, ESETCC IR-emit-order, parse_ctrl loop_top IR_NOP, IR_RAX_CLOBBER reads RCX, parse-time vs IR-time const-fold, NOP-fill preserves jumps, doc state-split (continued in v5_6_18_to_26_regalloc_arc_gotchas_bundle for Phase O4 + regalloc default-on)"
category = "cyrius"
---
=== IR-PASS BISECTION METHODOLOGY (v5.6.17 — load-bearing) ===

When an IR-walking pass (DCE, copy-prop, future peepholes) silently
corrupts cc5, do NOT keep guessing missing use/def cases by reading
code. The IR has too many opcodes and backend semantics to enumerate
from a desk read.

USE THIS PATTERN INSTEAD:

  1. Add a cap-env knob to the pass: CYRIUS_<PASS>_CAP=N limits
     the pass to its first N actions. Default = -1 (uncapped).
     Implementation in src/common/ir.cyr:

       fn ir_pass_capped(S, cap) {
           var actions = 0;
           ...
           if (cap >= 0) { if (actions >= cap) { dead = 0; } }
           ...
           actions = actions + 1;
       }
       fn ir_pass(S) { return ir_pass_capped(S, 0 - 1); }

  2. Add a per-action context dump in the pass:

       <PASS> action #N ni=X op=OP a1=A1 a2=A2 | ctx:
         <-prev3 <-prev2 <-prev1 ->next1 ->next2 ->next3

     (Skip IR_NOP / IR_ELIMINATED in prev/next walk so dump shows
      real-instruction context, not whitespace.)

  3. Binary-search by varying CYRIUS_<PASS>_CAP from 0 upward.
     Smallest N where cc5_b crashes = the action that's wrong.

  4. Inspect dump for action N. Opcode + 3 prev / 3 next ops will
     show the local pattern and what use/def case the pass missed.

WHY IT WORKS: the IR is small enough that 6 ops of context (3 each
side, NOP-filtered) shows the local pattern. The cap knob isolates
a single failing action so the dump output is manageable.

WHY GUESSING FAILED IN v5.6.16: two attempts at fixing DCE wasted
hours guessing missing-use cases (738 → 1,674 wrongly-killed
between attempts). v5.6.17 used the cap-knob methodology and found
the actual bug in ~10 minutes (kill #3 = MOV_CA before CLBRA).

KEEP THE KNOB: don't remove the cap env after the bug is fixed.
It's load-bearing for future audits when later passes (copy-prop,
dead-store, future peepholes) hit the same class of hidden semantic.

GENERALIZE: wire each new IR pass with its own cap on first
implementation, BEFORE turning the pass on. Const-fold could have
had CYRIUS_FOLD_CAP, copy-prop should have CYRIUS_COPYPROP_CAP, etc.

=== IR_RAX_CLOBBER READS RCX (v5.6.17 fix) ===

IR_RAX_CLOBBER is recorded by emit fns that mutate RAX (and possibly
RDX) without going through MOVR — specifically EMULH (mulh64),
EIDIV (idiv signed), ELODC (mov rax, [rcx]). The opcode name is
misleading — it doesn't ONLY clobber RAX. All three READ RCX:

  • EMULH:  reads rax, reads rcx, writes rax (hi half).
  • EIDIV:  reads rax (dividend low), reads rcx (divisor),
            writes rax (quotient), writes rdx (remainder).
  • ELODC:  reads rcx (the address), writes rax (the loaded value).

RCX is NEVER written by these — it's preserved across the op.

DCE liveness rules for IR_RAX_CLOBBER:
  • _ir_clobbers_rax(IR_RAX_CLOBBER) = 1   (writes rax)
  • _ir_uses_rax(IR_RAX_CLOBBER)     = 1   (reads rax — mulh/idiv)
  • _ir_def_rcx_any(IR_RAX_CLOBBER)  = 0   (does NOT write rcx)
  • _ir_uses_rcx(IR_RAX_CLOBBER)     = 1   (reads rcx — operand/divisor/address)

Same correction applies to:
  • IR_ADD_IMM_X1: rcx += imm — reads rcx, writes rcx. Both uses
    and def_rcx_any. Use case in PE arg-shuttle path.
  • IR_RAW_EMIT (v5.6.12 marker): opaque conservative — could read
    OR write any register. Treat as both reader and writer for
    RAX and RCX so DCE can't kill anything around it.

If you forget any of these correspondences, DCE will kill an
upstream MOV_CA whose RCX value the CLBRA needed.

=== ESETCC IR-EMIT-ORDER RULE (v5.6.15) ===

When an emit helper (Efoo) calls another emit helper (Ebar), and
both record their own IR opcodes via _IR_REC*, the order in which
they record matters. The IR stream must mirror the BYTE order in
codebuf — not the source-line order in the helper.

WRONG (IR says SETCC→CMP, bytes are cmp→setcc):

  fn ESETCC(S, op) {
      if (_IR_REC1(S, IR_SETCC, op) == 1) { return 0; }
      ECMPR(S);   # this records IR_CMP after we already recorded SETCC
      EB(S, 0x0F); ...
  }

RIGHT (IR matches byte order):

  fn ESETCC(S, op) {
      ECMPR(S);
      if (_IR_REC1(S, IR_SETCC, op) == 1) { return 0; }
      EB(S, 0x0F); ...
  }

WHY IT MATTERS: at IR_ENABLED=0 the bug is silent (IR not consumed).
At IR_ENABLED ≥ 1, any pass walking adjacent IR ops (peephole match,
liveness, dead-code) sees inverted order and either misses real
fusions or misclassifies live-ranges. v5.6.15 found 3,665 SETCC→CMP
IR adjacencies that were really cmp→setcc in bytes.

AUDIT RULE: every emit fn that calls another emit fn must record IR
AFTER the sub-call, not before. The IR sequence should read top-to-
bottom in the same order codebuf bytes appear.

=== PARSE_CTRL LOOP_TOP IR_NOP REQUIREMENT (v5.6.14) ===

When parse captures `loop_top = GCP(S)` for a back-edge target
(while/for/for-in/classic-for), it MUST also record an IR_NOP at
that position with arg1=loop_top:

  loop_top = GCP(S);
  if (_ire >= 1) { ir_emit(S, IR_NOP, 0, loop_top, 0); }

Without the IR_NOP marker, ir_build_bbs doesn't see a BB boundary
at the loop entry. JMP_BACK edges then land mid-BB, and any pass
that reasons about per-BB state (LASE, future copy-prop) will
incorrectly conclude that values from the BB's first-entry path
are still live during loop iterations.

v5.6.14 found this when re-enabling LASE: 811 LOAD_LOCAL eliminations
that all looked correct turned into 5,692 B of corruption because
the LOAD was redundant on first iteration but not on second.

PATTERN GENERALIZES: any back-edge target needs an IR_NOP landing
pad. Forward-jump targets (EPATCH) already get NOP markers via the
existing patch convention.

=== PARSE-TIME VS IR-TIME CONST-FOLD (v5.6.16) ===

Cyrius has TWO const-fold mechanisms now:

  1. PARSE-TIME via _cfo / _cfv flags in parse_expr.cyr
     Tracks single-side-literal fold: `5 * x`, `a + 7`, etc.
     Fires when LHS is a literal (`_cfo == 1`) and RHS is also
     a NUM token. Bytes-perfect in-place rewrite — uses SCP() to
     rewind CP and re-emit EMOVI(folded_val).

  2. IR-TIME via ir_const_fold() in ir.cyr (v5.6.16)
     Forward state-machine sweep over IR for the patterns parse-
     time missed: LOAD_IMM(a), PUSH, LOAD_IMM(b), [POP_RCX |
     MOV_CA + POP_RAX], OP. Two shapes covered (commutative
     after v5.6.10 shuttle elim, non-commutative). For each
     match: in-place rewrite codebuf — write EMOVI(fold_val) at
     LHS LOAD_IMM CP, NOP-fill remainder of span. Mark consumed
     IR nodes IR_NOP to keep IR consistent.

When to use which:

  • Parse-time is the right place when LHS is known literal at
    parse time (typical case). It rewinds CP — bytes shrink.
  • IR-time catches the long tail (e.g., when LHS comes from a
    fold that itself wasn't possible at parse-time, or when
    PARSE_TERM took a non-fold branch due to precedence). It
    rewrites in-place — bytes preserved (NOP-filled), real
    shrinkage waits for v5.6.22 codebuf compaction.

DON'T duplicate work: the IR pass should not re-detect what
parse-time already handled. v5.6.16 measurement: 130 IR folds vs
hundreds of parse-time folds — the IR pass is genuinely the long
tail.

=== NOP-FILL PRESERVES JUMP TARGETS + FIXUPS (v5.6.16 design choice) ===

All v5.6.x IR-level optimizations (LASE, const-fold, DCE, future
copy-prop) NOP-fill bytes in the codebuf rather than rewinding CP.
This is intentional:

  • Forward jumps (EPATCH) reference target offsets relative to
    end-of-jump-instruction. If we shifted bytes, we'd have to
    rewalk and patch every jump.
  • Backward jumps (JMP_BACK) similarly reference prior CPs.
  • The fixup table (FIXUP() at end of compile) references node
    CPs. Shifting would invalidate the table.
  • IR_NODE_CP records would need rebuilding.

NOP-fill sidesteps all of this — bytes don't move, jumps stay valid,
fixups still resolve. The cost: cc5 binary stays the same total size,
just with more 0x90 bytes. NOPs are decoded at near-zero µop cost on
modern CPUs, so runtime is unaffected.

REAL BINARY SHRINKAGE waits for v5.6.22 codebuf compaction — a single
pass at end of pipeline that:
  1. Walks codebuf for runs of ≥4 NOPs
  2. CP-rewinds past the run
  3. Shifts subsequent code down
  4. Fixes up forward jumps + fixup table CPs + IR_NODE_CP records

Doing compaction at end consolidates the work — one pass instead of
per-optimization. Plus jump+fixup repair is non-trivial; better to
get it right once than per-pass.

=== STATE-DOC SPLIT (v5.6.16 — process meta-lesson) ===

CLAUDE.md's "Current State" paragraph grew to 32 KB on a single line
because every release appended another sentence. Made it
unmaintainable for ingestion (token cost, parsability) and prone to
silent rot (version refs duplicated in 4 places).

THE FIX: split CLAUDE.md into preferences/process/procedures (durable,
~150 lines) + docs/development/state.md (volatile, refreshed every
release, ~50 lines). Historical narrative goes in
docs/development/completed-phases.md.

PATTERN GENERALIZES: any project's "instructions" doc that includes
"current state" is at risk. Watch for the rot:

  • A "Current State" or "Recent Changes" section that grows by
    one sentence per release.
  • Version numbers duplicated across multiple sections of the
    same doc.
  • Aspirational/historical content interleaved with durable rules.

When you see this pattern, propose a split. Durable rules in the
top-level instruction file; volatile state in a sibling refreshed-
per-release doc. The instruction file becomes preferences/process/
procedures only.

=== ROADMAP QUALITY-BEFORE-OPS RULE (v5.6.16/17 enforced) ===

When an optimization pass corrupts cc5 even after audit attempts,
SHIP what works correctly and BAIL on the broken piece. Don't
force in something that doesn't work just to hit a pre-planned slot.

v5.6.16 example: planned to ship const-fold + bitmap liveness + DCE
together (~260 LOC). Const-fold worked clean (130 folds / 774 B);
DCE corrupted cc5. Shipped const-fold alone, bailed on DCE,
re-pinned to v5.6.17 with proper investigation budget. v5.6.17 used
the bisection methodology (which itself became a saved pattern),
fixed in ~10 min, shipped clean (678 kills / 2,010 B).

THE BAD ALTERNATIVE: would have been to either ship broken DCE
(NOPE — cc5 wouldn't self-host), OR keep desk-reading missing-use
cases for hours/days (already failed twice in v5.6.16). The bisection
methodology was the third option that surfaced because of "STOP and
ask" — when stuck, propose both the small ship and the bigger fix.

DON'T SLIP UNILATERALLY: pinning the deferred half to a specific next
slot (v5.6.17, v5.6.18) is the user's call, not yours. Report
findings, propose options, wait for direction. The cascade is
acceptable IF the bug fix justifies its own slot — which it does for
correctness work.

[[entries]]
name = "v5_6_18_to_26_regalloc_arc_gotchas_bundle"
description = "v5.6.18 — v5.6.26 gotchas: regalloc default-on, Phase O4 split, SysV ECALLPOPS r12-r14 clobber, asm/regalloc layout collision, picker bisection methodology, EPOPARG cancel-mirror gap, Phase O5 maximal-munch dead end"
category = "cyrius"
---
v5.6.18 → v5.6.26 covered the optimization arc's Phase O4 (regalloc)
landing — including default-on flip — plus the v5.6.25 aarch64
push/pop-cancel completion that closed v5.6.11's mirror gap. Phase
O5 maximal-munch was tried at v5.6.26 scope but dropped (recon
found 0 fused-op candidates; push-imm rewrite has rax-side-effect +
forward-jump-target issues; needs an IR-level push-elision pass
first).

=== CODEGEN SCRATCH REGS MUST BE CALLER-SAVED (v5.6.24) ===

The biggest landmine in the regalloc default-on landing.
`src/backend/x86/emit.cyr::ECALLPOPS` SysV n>6 stack-arg shuttle
used **r12, r13, r14 as scratch** to pop extras across the 6
reg-arg pops. r11 was correctly caller-saved; r12-r14 are
CALLEE-SAVED in SysV. Pre-regalloc, that was safe-by-accident
because cyrius didn't emit r12-r15 anywhere. Once v5.6.20+
regalloc started pinning caller's locals to those exact
callee-saved regs, every 8+ arg call silently corrupted the
locals — caller's pinned `fs` was overwritten with a popped arg
value before the call, callee preserved (the wrong) value, and
the caller continued with garbage.

Surfaced as TWO bisection-disjoint reports:
1. flags.tcyr at AUTO_CAP=118 — the 118th auto-enabled fn
   (`test_str_short`) had an `_argv(3, "prog", "-o", "/tmp/out.s",
   0, 0, 0, 0, 0)` 9-arg call; the shuttle clobbered r12 holding
   `fs` in the next-fn `test_defaults`'s frame; flags_get_int
   returned 0 instead of the registered default 7.
2. sandhi M2 (filed 2026-04-24, same date-case file) —
   sandhi_http_response_parse's `var headers` silently zeroed by
   an unrelated downstream call. Workaround was
   `var hdr_backup = headers;` (shifted local layout away from
   picker's choice).

Same root. Fix: rewrote SysV ECALLPOPS to use **only r10
(caller-saved)** via direct `[rsp+offset]` MOV addressing — no
pops, single shift loop, end with `add rsp, 48`. Length-equal to
the un-rewritten path.

**Audit rule for new codegen** (load-bearing): any register used
as scratch in cyrius codegen MUST be caller-saved in the target
ABI, OR be explicitly saved/restored. SysV caller-saved scratch:
rax/rcx/rdx/rsi/rdi/r8/r9/r10/r11. Win64 caller-saved scratch:
rax/rcx/rdx/r8/r9/r10/r11. Avoid rbx/r12-r15 unless wrapping with
push+pop pairs (and accounting for the rsp shift in nearby
[rsp+N] references).

=== "ALIGNMENT REGRESSION" CAN BE A RED HERRING (v5.6.23) ===

v5.6.22's default-on flip surfaced what looked like a v5.5.21
array-alignment regression — `regression-inline-asm-discard.sh`
SIGSEGV'd on PXOR xmm,m128 over `var rk[240]`. The shape said
"alignment". v5.6.23 investigation had to PROBE the array VA
(`mod 16 = 0` — fine) before discarding the alignment framing.

Real cause: `regalloc's prologue saves rbx/r12-r15 to [rbp-8]..
[rbp-40]`, and `parse_fn.cyr` computes local-var disps as
`-(idx + 1 + _cur_fn_regalloc) * 8`, shifting every spilled
local/param 40 B further from rbp. Inline asm hardcodes
`mov rdi, [rbp-0x08]` to read param 1 under the standard cyrius
prologue. Under auto-enable that read the saved RBX value (a
pointer-shaped garbage) which PXOR then dereferenced.

Fix: `parse_fn.cyr` body-scan lookahead for token 48 (`asm`).
Auto-enable silently skips fns with asm; opt-in `#regalloc`
on an asm fn warns and skips. Stdlib callers protected:
`lib/fnptr.cyr`, `lib/thread.cyr`, `lib/atomic.cyr`,
`lib/hashmap_fast.cyr`, `lib/u128.cyr`, `lib/thread_local.cyr`,
`lib/fdlopen.cyr`, `lib/args_macos.cyr`.

**Generalized rule**: when symptom is a memop SIGSEGV under new
codegen and the obvious culprit looks like an existing fix's
edge case, probe the operand's actual address FIRST. If the
alignment/size/value is correct, the bug is elsewhere in the
pipeline — usually layout or register choice.

=== PICKER TIME-SHARE BREAKS LOOPS (v5.6.22) ===

v5.6.20's Poletto-Sarkar picker added time-sliced register reuse:
when an interval expires, its register can be reassigned to a
later interval. SAFE for straight-line forward execution. UNSAFE
for any backward CFG edge (loops): JMP_BACK to a position INSIDE
an EARLIER interval re-reads the register expecting the earlier
value but finds the new (time-shared) one.

Surfaced at v5.6.22 auto-enable bisection on
`PP_ALREADY_INCLUDED`'s nested while loops:
- rbx assigned to `cnt` for [135876, 135900] — covered the
  `while (i < cnt)` condition LOAD inside the outer loop
- After lidx=2 expired, rbx reassigned to `p` for [135963, 136057]
- Outer loop iteration JMP_BACK re-executed the cnt LOAD at
  CP 135900 — but rbx now held `p`'s value
- Wrong loop count → infinite loop / wrong branch

**Fix**: extend `interval.last_cp = ra_end` for every interval —
picker can no longer time-share registers (intervals never expire
before fn end). Effectively single-register-per-local-for-whole-fn
= greedy-equivalent. Proper time-sharing needs cross-BB liveness
analysis (extend last_cp through backward CFG edges) — pinned
future slot.

=== PHASE O4 SPLIT (v5.6.19/20/22 — 1→3 slots) ===

Originally pinned as full Poletto-Sarkar linear-scan in one slot
(~600-900 LOC). Structural reality: no vreg layer, no cross-BB
liveness, every emit fn hardcoded RAX/RCX. Made one-slot
infeasible. Split into:
- v5.6.19 = Phase O4a: per-fn live-interval infra (ra_first/ra_last
  arrays, dump knob). Ships intervals; no codegen change. Also
  fixed a pre-existing v4.8.4 latent sizing bug — `ra_counts[256]`
  was 256 BYTES (32 i64 slots) but write loop wrote 256 i64s;
  overflow into adjacent global memory; existing peephole tolerated
  it because high-idx use-counts default to 0; interval tracking
  needed correct sizing.
- v5.6.20 = Phase O4b: Poletto-Sarkar picker. Replaces v4.8.4
  greedy use-count picker. Insertion-sort intervals by first_cp
  (deterministic tie-break by lidx), walk forward, expire active
  intervals, assign free reg or spill furthest-next-use.
  CYRIUS_REGALLOC_PICKER_CAP=N from day 1 for bisection.
- v5.6.22 = Phase O4c (partial): auto-enable infra DISABLED by
  default + picker correctness fix (loop-back time-share — extend
  last_cp = ra_end). Default-on attempt at this slot surfaced two
  bugs: (1) inline-asm layout collision (fixed v5.6.23); (2) ECALLPOPS
  r12-r14 clobber (fixed v5.6.24).
- v5.6.24 = default-on flip + the ECALLPOPS rewrite.

**Lesson**: when a pinned slot is structurally infeasible after recon,
SPLIT into legitimate phases (cascading +N is fine) rather than
band-aiding or scope-cutting. Bandaids/threshold tweaks/auto-enable+
patch are shortcuts. Splits are pre-planned decompositions.

=== EPOPARG MIRROR GAP (v5.6.25 — aarch64 push/pop-cancel completion) ===

v5.6.9 shipped push/pop-cancel for x86 (381 pairs eliminated).
v5.6.11's memory said "aarch64 mirror fires too" — but only the
EPOPR path. EPOPARG(S, n) emits the SAME `ldr xN, [sp], #16` for
N=0..7. For N=0 the encoding is identical to EPOPR's pop-x0
(0xF84107E0). EPOPR did the v5.6.9 adjacency check; EPOPARG
DIDN'T. Every 1-arg call site (EPUSHR; ECALLPOPS(1) → EPOPARG(S, 0))
paid 8 bytes of redundant push+pop.

Bytescan recon under v5.6.24 default-on regalloc found 2,569 such
pairs in native aarch64 cc5. 13-LOC fix in EPOPARG mirroring
EPOPR's `GCP == _last_push_cp` rewind, gated on `n == 0`. Native
aarch64 cc5 **517,376 → 497,008 B (−20,368 B / −3.94%)** — bigger
than v5.6.11's combine-shuttle shrinkage.

**Audit pattern when reusing a documented optimization**: when an
existing fix is documented as "also fires for X", verify ALL emit
paths for X — not just the primary one. Mirror-gap bugs hide in
the secondary paths that nobody re-audited.

=== PHASE O5 MAXIMAL-MUNCH DEAD END (v5.6.26-attempted, dropped) ===

Phase O5 was originally pinned for v5.6.26 (after Phase O4
regalloc landed). Goal: fuse adjacent operations into single
instructions (mul+add → MADD on aarch64; mov-imm + push →
push-imm on x86). Recon under v5.6.24 default-on regalloc:
- aarch64 mul+add adjacent pairs: **0** across cc5_native_arm + 8
  math-heavy tcyr tests (bigint, u128, mulh64, keccak, sha1, base64,
  hashmap, vec). cyrius's stack-machine IR keeps a `str x0, [sp,
  #-16]!` between every sub-expression result and consumer, so
  `mul+add` pairs are SEPARATED by push/pop pairs. Fusion window
  doesn't open without a separate IR-level push-elision pass.
- x86 push-imm fusion (`mov eax, imm32; push rax` → `push imm32`):
  2,861 sites in cc5 (recon), but rewriting fails because EMOVI
  has a SIDE EFFECT (sets rax = imm) that subsequent code may
  read. Forward jumps patched by EPATCH land at the post-EMOVI
  position; rewriting changes what's at that position semantically.
  ~71% of sites have ambiguous rax usage by conservative heuristic.

**Pinned long-term, no slot**. Both branches need an IR-level
push-elision pass to make the fusion windows actually open. v5.6.26
shipped peephole refinement + doc completion instead.

=== BISECTION METHODOLOGY (saved v5.6.17, used v5.6.22 + v5.6.24) ===

The v5.6.17 IR-pass bisection pattern (CYRIUS_<PASS>_CAP=N env knob
+ binary-search) keeps paying dividends. v5.6.22 used
CYRIUS_REGALLOC_AUTO_CAP=N + CYRIUS_REGALLOC_PICKER_CAP=N to
narrow time-share bug to "PP_ALREADY_INCLUDED + 3rd reassignment"
in ~10 minutes. v5.6.24 used the same knob to narrow the
ECALLPOPS bug to "test_str_short = 118th auto-enabled fn + its
9-arg _argv call". Both saved hours.

**Pattern for new codegen passes**: ship a CAP env knob in the
SAME slot as the pass itself, not later. Costs ~5 LOC, makes
bisection trivial when something breaks.

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib_alloc_grow_step_vs_requested_size"
description = "Bump-allocator grow logic must cover the requested allocation, not a fixed delta — fixed step `0x100000` regardless of requested size returned pointers past the brk/mmap for any alloc(>1MB)"
category = "cyrius"
---
BUG SHAPE: The cyrius stdlib bump allocator (`lib/alloc.cyr`,
`lib/alloc_macos.cyr`) grew the heap by exactly `0x100000`
whenever `_heap_ptr` crossed `_heap_end`, regardless of how far
past the new pointer was. Any single `alloc(size > 1 MB)` near
the grow boundary returned a pointer past the newly-mapped
region — `alloc()` reported success, and the caller's first
tail-write SIGSEGV'd at an unmapped address.

Pre-fix (Linux brk path):
    _heap_ptr = new_ptr;
    if (_heap_ptr > _heap_end) {
        var new_end = _heap_end + 0x100000;   // fixed delta
        var result = syscall(12, new_end);
        ...
        _heap_end = new_end;
    }
    return ptr;                                // past new _heap_end

Post-fix (v5.6.34 Linux):
    var new_end = (_heap_ptr + 0xFFFFF) & (0 - 0x100000);
    // round up to next 1MB grain; one brk per grow covers any size

Post-fix (v5.6.34 macOS):
    while (_heap_end < _heap_ptr) {
        // loop 1MB mmaps; preserves per-step contiguity guard
        // (a single hinted mmap can legitimately return a
        // different base for larger requests)
    }

WHERE IT BIT: sit v0.6.1 S-33 triage. The 16 MiB zlib retry
buffer in `object_db.cyr:read_object` allocates in one call
via `alloc(16 * 1024 * 1024)`. On a 100-commit fixture, the
grow boundary fell inside this allocation — SIGSEGV on first
write into the tail past the 1 MB mapped region.

BROADER LESSON: any bump-allocator grow step must compare
against the requested allocation size, not a hardcoded delta.
The fixed-step pattern is fine ONLY when the hot path is
known to be many small allocations; the moment a consumer
does one large allocation, the pattern silently miscompiles
into returned-pointer-past-mapped-region.

DETECTION: `tests/tcyr/alloc_grow.tcyr` covers this directly
(4 MB + 16 MB tail-writes + 1000×64 B after jumbos + 128 MB
single block). Extend when adding new alloc paths.

RELATED LATENT SUSPECT: sit's same 2026-04-24 ticket reports
a second symptom — `sit fsck` reports ~20% of objects
unreadable after the grow fix — which MAY be a different
cyrius stdlib memory-corruption mode (stale pointer /
double-commit in the bump allocator beyond the grow bug),
or a dep-layer bug (patra / sankoch). Pinned as v5.6.35
triage; do not assume it's a cyrius bug without the
prescribed patra bytes-roundtrip + sankoch symmetry first.

[[entries]]
name = "sit_symptom_2_was_sankoch_encoder_not_cyrius"
description = "v5.6.35 — sit's 'fsck reports unreadable objects at scale' was a sankoch deflate encoder bug, not a cyrius alloc bug. Triage methodology that pinned it: standalone replay of dumped buffers + in-process roundtrip instrumentation + per-row checksum around dep boundary calls."
category = "cyrius"
---
PROBLEM SHAPE: sit reported "after fixing the alloc grow bug,
20% of objects come back unreadable at scale, first bad at ~commit
15, scales with N." Three plausible layers (patra / sankoch /
cyrius latent corruption) — fix-before-triage forbidden.

WHAT THE TRIAGE LOOKED LIKE (cyrius v5.6.35):

1. Reproduce the failure end-to-end. Build sit against current
   cyrius + deps, run the 100-commit fixture, confirm the
   reported failure rate (53/247 unreadable on the documented
   fixture).

2. Eliminate patra: write a standalone cyrius program that
   exercises patra with sit-shaped row inserts (STR + INT +
   BYTES schema) at the failure scale. 1600+ rows across
   single-process, cross-session (close+reopen), query-then-
   insert, and cross-process patterns — all clean. Rules out
   patra.

3. Eliminate cyrius alloc: instrument sit's `write_typed_object`
   with a pre/post checksum of the `compressed` buffer around
   the `patra_insert_row` call. Match across all 300 inserts
   means the buffer isn't being mutated in transit. Rules out
   in-call buffer mutation by the dep boundary.

4. Eliminate sit-side aliasing: in the same sit instrumentation,
   add an in-process `zlib_decompress(compressed, clen, ...)`
   immediately after `zlib_compress` returns the positive
   `clen`. If THAT fails (50/300 did) — bug is in the encoder
   for those specific inputs, not in any post-encoder buffer
   handling.

5. Confirm input-determinism: dump every `<hash>.full` and
   `<hash>.cz` to sidecar files. Replay each `.full` through
   sankoch in a fresh process (no patra, no sit, no cyrius
   pressure). 50/300 fail standalone with byte-identical output
   to what sit produced. Encoder is deterministic on input.

6. Save the smallest failing input as a minimal repro
   (~50-line standalone cyrius program reading the bytes from
   stdin and asserting roundtrip). Hand off to sankoch.

WHAT IT WASN'T:
- Not patra. patra ROUNDTRIPS bytes correctly.
- Not cyrius alloc. v5.6.34's grow fix was sufficient for
  alloc-side correctness; the 50/300 failures persist with
  v5.6.34's fix in place.
- Not sit-side. Sit passes the right buffer + length to patra;
  the buffer isn't mutated in transit; the buffer can't be
  decompressed even microseconds after compress returns in the
  same process under the same lock.

WHY THE BUG DIDN'T SHOW IN SANKOCH'S OWN TEST SUITE: sankoch's
roundtrip tests use synthetic byte patterns (random fills,
text-like fills) that don't trigger the bad symbol distribution
the encoder mishandles. The bug needed sit's tree-object byte
shape (mix of `100644 file_<i>.txt\0` ASCII + 32-byte binary
hashes per entry) at specific lengths to surface. Lesson: a
roundtrip-test-corpus that doesn't include real consumer-shape
inputs has dead spots.

RESOLUTION: 3 sankoch tags (2.0.1 → 2.0.2 fixed 51/53; 2.0.3
fixed remaining 2). Cyrius v5.6.35 = dep-pin bump 2.0.1 → 2.0.3
in `cyrius.cyml` + active `tests/regression-sit-status.sh` gate.

GENERALIZE: when triaging a "consumer X reports issue Y at
scale" against a stack of deps, the dump-and-replay pattern
turns multi-layer state-interaction bugs into single-layer
deterministic repros. Save: input-to-suspect, output-of-suspect,
and the calling-program's pre/post state if relevant. Replay
each in isolation. The layer that reproduces the failure with
NONE of the calling state is the layer that owns the bug.

[[entries]]
name = "two_consecutive_platform_drift_pins_were_both_fn_main_fixture_bugs"
description = "v5.6.33 (Mach-O) and v5.6.36 (PE) — two consecutive 'platform drift' regression pins on cyrius's roadmap turned out to be the SAME test-fixture bug, not actual compiler regressions"
category = "cyrius"
---
PATTERN OBSERVED: v5.6.33 and v5.6.36 were both pinned as
"platform drift" regressions — Mach-O syscall(60,42) exits 1 not
42 on macOS Sequoia (v5.6.33), PE syscall(60,42) exits 0x40010080
not 42 on Win11 24H2 (v5.6.36). Both attributed to OS loader
hardening (Sequoia dyld strictness, 24H2 CET shadow-stack /
DllCharacteristics enforcement). Both turned out to be the SAME
test-fixture bug.

THE FIXTURE BUG: each gate's source used
  fn main() { syscall(60, 42); return 0; }

In cyrius this is a function definition that is NEVER CALLED.
There is no auto-invoked `main()`. Top-level statements ARE the
program entry. With no top-level code, the entry prologue's
branch-over-fn-bodies (patched by `EJMP0`/`EPATCH`) lands on the
EEXIT/EEXIT_PE tail, which calls the platform's exit routine with
whatever happened to be in the arg-slot register / x0:
- macOS arm64: BSD `_exit(x0)` — x0 = argc (= 1 from shell) → rc=1.
- Linux x86_64: `exit(rax)` syscall — rax content varies.
- Windows PE: `kernel32!ExitProcess(rcx)` — rcx may have inherited
  state from runtime, on Win11 24H2 it landed on 0x40010080 (an
  NTSTATUS-shape value with high-nibble 0x4 =
  STATUS_SEVERITY_INFORMATIONAL, which made PowerShell report
  `ApplicationFailedException` instead of a plain non-zero
  exit code).

THE 30-SECOND CHECK that disproves both:
  $ cat <<EOF | cc5 > /tmp/probe; chmod +x /tmp/probe
  syscall(60, 42);
  EOF
  $ /tmp/probe; echo $?
  42

If THAT exits 42, the platform/loader/codegen is fine and the
gate's `fn main()` fixture is the only bug.

V5.6.36 ALSO VERIFIED: on Win11 24H2, patching the cyrius-
emitted PE's DllCharacteristics from 0x0000 (no flags) →
0x0160 (DYNAMIC_BASE | NX_COMPAT | HIGH_ENTROPY_VA) produced
byte-identical exit behavior — both forms exit 42 with the
corrected source, both exit 0x40010080 with the broken source.
**Win11 24H2 does NOT require security flags.** That whole
suspect class was wrong.

GENERALIZED RULE (already in feedback memory
`feedback_verify_slot_premise_first.md`): when triaging
"platform drift since vX.Y.Z" reports for cyrius, FIRST
verify the test fixture exercises what it claims to test.
The 30-second top-level-syntax probe is cheaper than ANY
investigation premise based on the broken fixture.

WHY IT KEPT HAPPENING: gate fixture authors who came from C/Rust
backgrounds wrote `fn main()` assuming entry-point convention
that doesn't exist in cyrius. The same pattern bit two
consecutive gate authors. v5.6.33 and v5.6.36 both ship with the
fixture rewrite + a CHANGELOG paragraph explicitly documenting
the misdiagnosis class.

PINNED FOR FUTURE: when adding a regression gate that needs to
"return value N from a cyrius program", use `syscall(60, N)` at
top level, not `fn main() { syscall(60, N); return 0; }`. If the
gate needs a helper function, define it then call it from
top-level:
  fn add3(a, b, c) { return a + b + c; }
  syscall(60, add3(10, 20, 12));

[[entries]]
name = "libssl_needs_fdlopen_not_dynlib_open"
description = "v5.6.37 — libssl's OPENSSL_init_ssl uses a recursive pthread mutex whose __kind field lives in the glibc TCB. cyrius's dynlib_bootstrap_tls zeroed TCB reads __kind=0 (non-recursive); same-thread re-entry deadlocks on futex."
category = "cyrius"
---
WHAT BREAKS: pre-v5.6.37 `lib/tls.cyr::_tls_init` loaded libssl
via `dynlib_open` on top of `dynlib_bootstrap_tls`'s 4096-byte
zeroed TCB + `arch_prctl(ARCH_SET_FS)`. That's enough for
`%fs:N` reads and IFUNC resolvers. It is NOT enough for libssl.

libssl 3's `OPENSSL_init_ssl` uses a recursive pthread mutex
inside the glibc TCB. The mutex's `__kind` field (offset varies
by glibc version, but it's in the TCB region) determines
whether a same-thread re-entry is legal. On a real
glibc-initialised process, `__kind = PTHREAD_MUTEX_RECURSIVE_NP`
(= 1) because `__libc_pthread_init` set it. On cyrius's zeroed
stub, `__kind = 0 = PTHREAD_MUTEX_TIMED_NP` (non-recursive).
libssl re-enters → CAS 0→1 (acquire), CAS 0→1 fails (already
held), CAS 1→2 (mark contended), `futex(mutex, WAIT, 2, NULL)`.
Single-threaded process → nothing wakes it → indefinite hang.

Symptom: `strace` shows
`futex(0x??cc118, FUTEX_WAIT_PRIVATE, 2, NULL)` with no
subsequent syscalls. The futex address falls inside cyrius's
bump heap (same range as `dynlib_bootstrap_tls`'s TCB).

FIX (shipped v5.6.37): route libssl through `fdlopen`, not
`dynlib_open`. `fdlopen_init_full` invokes
`~/.cyrius/dlopen-helper` through the real
`ld-linux-x86-64.so.2`, which runs `_dl_start` +
`__libc_start_main` + full `__libc_pthread_init`. By the
time control returns to cyrius, the process has a
fully-initialised glibc TCB (DTV, stack_guard,
pthread_kind, `__libc_multiple_threads`, the whole set).
Subsequent `dlopen("libssl.so.3")` (via
`fdlopen_dlopen(state)`) loads libssl against real glibc;
all pthread primitives work.

WHEN YOU NEED FDLOPEN VS DYNLIB:
- **Use `dynlib_open`** for libraries whose symbols cyrius
  calls but that don't need real pthread state — libresolv
  for DNS lookups, libcrypto for isolated hash/AES calls
  (no init_ssl-style recursive mutex), libsystemd for
  journal writes, etc.
- **Use `fdlopen_dlopen`** for libraries that use pthread
  primitives as part of their own init — libssl, libpq,
  libcurl, anything that calls `pthread_once` /
  `pthread_mutex_lock` with recursive expectation during
  startup. If you're not sure, fdlopen is safe; dynlib is
  faster but brittle.

CONSUMER REQUIREMENT (v5.6.37+): `lib/tls.cyr` no longer
auto-includes `lib/fdlopen.cyr` because cyrius's preprocessor
expanded-output cap is 1 MB and heavy stdlib consumers
(`tests/tcyr/large_input.tcyr`) already run at 98%. Callers
of `lib/tls.cyr` MUST include fdlopen.cyr first:

    include "lib/fdlopen.cyr"   # ← required as of v5.6.37
    include "lib/tls.cyr"

Without the fdlopen include, cc5 warns about undefined
functions (`fdlopen_helper_available`, `fdlopen_init_full`,
etc.) and the binary SIGILLs on the first `tls_available()`
call.

DEBUGGING PATTERN FOR FUTURE PTHREAD-STUB-DEADLOCK BUGS:
1. `strace -f` the hanging program. Find the last futex
   with no subsequent syscalls.
2. Match the futex address against `/proc/<pid>/maps`.
3. If it falls inside cyrius's bump heap (TCB region), the
   library's pthread primitive is using stub-TCB state.
4. The fix is either (a) extend the stub to cover whatever
   field the library reads, or (b) switch to fdlopen so the
   library gets a real glibc.
5. (a) is version-specific and fragile; (b) works once the
   fdlopen helper is installed.

[[entries]]
name = "version_string_must_not_be_hardcoded_in_source"
description = "v5.6.39 — cc5 --version drifted at 5.6.29-1 for 9 releases because the version was hardcoded in src/main.cyr and version-bump.sh's regex didn't match the -N hotfix suffix. Fix: route through auto-generated src/version_str.cyr; never hardcode versions in source."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: any version string baked at compile time MUST come from
an auto-generated file the bump script writes via heredoc, NOT
from a hardcoded source literal updated via regex sed.

WHY: the regex shape is brittle to suffix conventions. cyrius's
version-bump.sh used a grep gate:

    grep -Eq '"cc5 [0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\\n"' src/main.cyr

That matches `X.Y.Z\n` but not `X.Y.Z-N\n`. When v5.6.29-1
shipped (hotfix suffix per the documented `-N` convention),
the literal `"cc5 5.6.29-1\n"` no longer matched the gate.
The grep returned empty, the sed was skipped, and the bump
emitted `warning: no cc5 version string found in src/main.cyr`
to stderr — silently logged, never escalated. The bump
"succeeded" but the literal stayed at 5.6.29-1. Subsequent
9 bumps repeated the same silent failure. `cc5 --version`
got stuck at `5.6.29-1` until a USER caught it via Starship
prompt observation.

`src/main_win.cyr` had the same bug shape with WORSE drift:
the bumper only ever swept `main.cyr`, never `main_win.cyr`,
so `cc5_win --version` had been stuck at `5.5.0` since
v5.5.0 ever shipped.

WRONG FIX: extend the regex to `[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+(-[0-9]+)?\\n`
to accept the `-N` suffix. Re-introduces the same bug class
for any future suffix shape (`-rc1`, `-pre`, `-alpha2`,
date-stamp suffixes, etc.). The bug class is "version string
in source = brittle".

RIGHT FIX (shipped v5.6.39): eliminate hardcoded literals.
Generate `src/version_str.cyr` from `VERSION` via heredoc.
Sources `include` the generated file and reference vars.
No regex, no per-file sweeping, no suffix vulnerability.

GENERALIZED RULE: any time a build script's job is to "rewrite
a literal in source", consider whether the literal can be
moved to a generated include file instead. Generated files
are simple (heredoc, single-pass write); regex-rewriting
literals is a fragile pattern that drifts silently the moment
the source format violates the regex's assumptions.

DETECTION (look for these patterns when triaging build-script
issues):

    if grep -Eq 'PATTERN' source-file; then
        sed -i ...
    else
        echo "warning: pattern not found"
    fi

This shape is the silent-drift recipe. Replace with:

    cat > generated-file <<EOF
    var X = "$NEW";
    var X_LEN = ${#NEW};
    EOF

And `include` the generated file from the source.

BUMP SCRIPT MUST REGENERATE ON SAME-VERSION INVOCATION too —
otherwise the documented "regenerate without bumping" path
silently no-ops. cyrius's version-bump.sh moves the
`src/version_str.cyr` write BEFORE the
`if [ "$NEW" = "$OLD" ]; then exit 0; fi` early-exit gate.

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib_tls_hook_surface_via_fn_pointer_not_callback_registry"
description = "v5.6.40 — lib/tls.cyr exposes ALPN/mTLS via tls_connect_with_ctx_hook(sock, host, hook_fp, hook_ctx) + tls_dlsym(name) instead of registering callbacks per concern (set_alpn / set_verify / set_cert). One hook fn-pointer + one symbol-resolver = bounded surface; consumers compose freely."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: when a stdlib module wraps a C library that exposes
N configuration knobs (ALPN, mTLS, verify cb, session
tickets, SNI override, ...), do NOT mirror N knobs into
the stdlib API. Expose ONE pre-handshake hook that runs on
the underlying object, plus ONE symbol-resolver that hands
the consumer the raw C function pointers from the
already-loaded library. Two surface elements. Done.

WHY: per-knob mirroring (`tls_set_alpn(ctx, list)`,
`tls_set_verify(ctx, cb)`, `tls_set_cert(ctx, cert, key)`,
...) explodes the stdlib's surface area linearly with
demand. Each new sandhi/ARK/whatever consumer that needs
something cyrius didn't anticipate becomes a new stdlib
slot — and the stdlib starts encoding library-specific
domain knowledge (what ALPN protocol-list bytes look like,
what the verify callback ABI is) it has no business owning.

The hook approach inverts that: cyrius owns "we have a
TLS connection in progress and you can configure its
SSL_CTX before SSL_new fires". The CONSUMER owns "I want
to set ALPN protocols using SSL_CTX_set_alpn_protos with
this specific byte string". `tls_dlsym` lets the consumer
reach the underlying lib's symbol without re-bootstrapping
fdlopen on every call (the stdlib already holds the handle
from `_tls_init`).

CONCRETE SHAPE (v5.6.40):

    fn alpn_hook(user_data, ssl_ctx) {
        var fn_set = tls_dlsym("SSL_CTX_set_alpn_protos");
        return fncall3(fn_set, ssl_ctx, &alpn_bytes, 12);
    }
    var tls = tls_connect_with_ctx_hook(fd, host, &alpn_hook, 0);

Stdlib does NOT know what ALPN is. The consumer encodes the
1-byte-length-prefixed protocol list, calls
`SSL_CTX_set_alpn_protos` directly via `tls_dlsym`, returns
0/non-zero to signal continue/abort. mTLS is the same shape
with `SSL_CTX_use_certificate_file` + `SSL_CTX_use_PrivateKey_file`.

WHEN TO USE THIS PATTERN: stdlib module wraps a foreign
library where (a) the library's own configuration surface
is wide and growing (OpenSSL, libcurl, libsqlite3,
libuv, ...), and (b) cyrius has no architectural reason to
own the per-knob semantics. Expose handle + hook + dlsym;
let consumers compose.

WHEN NOT TO USE: when cyrius DOES want to own the
semantics (e.g., `lib/syscalls.cyr` deliberately hides
arch differences — exposing a "syscall hook" would
defeat the abstraction).

GENERALIZED API SHAPE for foreign-library stdlib wrappers:

    <module>_<verb>_with_<thing>_hook(args, hook_fp, hook_ctx)
    <module>_dlsym(name) -> fnptr

The default `<module>_<verb>(args)` becomes a 1-line
wrapper passing zeros — no behavior change for existing
callers.

[[entries]]
name = "sysv_odd_stack_args_rsp_alignment_violation"
description = "v5.6.41 — SysV ABI requires rsp 16-aligned at every CALL (so callee sees rsp+8 16-aligned at entry). Cyrius's ECALLPOPS for n>6 args used add rsp, 48 unconditionally; for odd nextra (N=7,9,11) this left rsp 8-aligned at CALL, propagating misalignment until something downstream did SSE on a stack-saved value (libssl/libc prologs) and SIGSEGV'd at first instruction. Win64 path was already correct via framesize-mod-15 alignment branch; SysV path missed it."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: when a cyrius function takes more than 6 formal params,
the 7th+ arg goes on the stack via SysV. For an ODD number of
stack args (N=7, 9, 11), the caller-side push sequence + the
existing `add rsp, 48` cleanup leaves rsp 8-aligned at the
CALL instruction — violating the SysV ABI rule that `(%rsp+8)
must be 16-aligned at function entry`.

The misalignment is silent under cyrius-only call chains
because cyrius prologs don't use SSE. It only surfaces when
something downstream — typically a libssl / libc fn whose
prolog uses `movdqa` / SSE saves on stack-saved values —
faults at its first instruction.

DETECTION: a SIGSEGV reported as "at the first instruction
of an extern symbol" called from a fn with 7+ params is the
canonical signature. Pre-v5.6.41, sandhi's `tls_connect`
from a 7-param `sandhi_conn_open_fully_timed` SIGSEGV'd
inside libssl's prolog — exactly this shape.

ABI MATH: SysV says `(%rsp+8) is 16-aligned at function
entry`. Means `%rsp` itself = 8 mod 16 (the +8 accounts for
the retaddr the CALL just pushed). Means before the CALL,
`%rsp` must be 16-aligned (so retaddr-push leaves it 8-aligned
at entry).

WIN64 vs SysV: Win64's `ECALLPOPS` always allocates
`framesize = 32 (shadow) + nextra*8`, rounded up to 16:

    if ((framesize & 15) != 0) { framesize = framesize + 8; }

That's the alignment branch SysV was missing. SysV's path
emitted `add rsp, 48` regardless, leaving:

    rsp_after_pops = rsp_after_n_pushes + 48
                   = R - N*8 + 48
                   = R - (N-6)*8

For nextra = N - 6:
- nextra = 1: rsp = R - 8 (8-aligned, BAD)
- nextra = 2: rsp = R - 16 (16-aligned, OK)
- nextra = 3: rsp = R - 24 (8-aligned, BAD)
- nextra = 4: rsp = R - 32 (16-aligned, OK)
- nextra = 5: rsp = R - 40 (8-aligned, BAD)

FIX SHAPE: for odd nextra, shift step-2 stack writes from
`[rsp + (6+i)*8]` down to `[rsp + (5+i)*8]` AND change the
final `add rsp, 48` to `add rsp, 40`. This drops one fewer
reg-arg slot, lands the extras at the SAME `[rbp+16+...]`
offsets in the callee from rbp's POV after CALL+push rbp
+mov rbp,rsp, AND keeps rsp 16-aligned at the CALL site.
ECALLCLEAN releases the corresponding 8 bytes of alignment
padding in the symmetric branch.

WRONG FIX (caught by `tests/tcyr/fncall_ceiling.tcyr` in
v5.6.41 first-attempt): `add rsp, 48; sub rsp, 8` after the
existing logic. This DOES align rsp but moves the stack args
8 bytes higher in the caller frame, so callee reads them at
`[rbp+24]` instead of `[rbp+16]` — alignment fixed, layout
broken. Right answer changes both the writes AND the final
sp-adjust together, so the args land at the same callee-side
offsets while rsp still ends 16-aligned.

DETECTION (codebase-side): grep `ECALLPOPS` and look for any
caller-side calling-convention logic that doesn't have a
parity check on the total arg count. Win64's pattern (always
align to 16 via framesize-mod-15) is the reference.

SELF-HOST FIXPOINT IS NECESSARY BUT NOT SUFFICIENT: cc5's
3-step self-host (cc5_a → cc5_b → cc5_c byte-identical)
verifies codegen DETERMINISM, not codegen CORRECTNESS for
ABI rules cc5 itself doesn't trigger. cc5 callees don't use
SSE in their prologues, so an alignment bug stays latent
until a downstream consumer (sandhi via libssl) hits it.
After any change to ECALLPOPS / ECALLCLEAN /
ESTORESTACKPARM, run `tests/tcyr/fncall_ceiling.tcyr` AND
`tests/tcyr/sysv_odd_stack_args.tcyr` (which has callers
with 7/8/9/10/11 params hitting an SSE-using leaf).

[[entries]]
name = "pp_ifdef_pass_helpers_must_take_src_base"
description = "v5.6.42 — same-class fix as v5.6.30. PP_IFDEF_PASS copies preprocessed content back to S+0 capped at 524288 B; helpers (PP_HASH/PP_DEFINE/PP_DEFINED/PP_GETVAL/PP_EVAL_IF) reading via S+pos for source > 524288 B land in stale heap. v5.6.30 fixed PP_DERIVE_*; v5.6.42 closed the rest by threading src_base through the family."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: `lex_pp.cyr`'s `PP_IFDEF_PASS` operates on a `tmp`
mmap buffer (full uncapped size, can be up to the 2 MB
preprocess_out limit) but copies the source back to `S+0`
capped at 524288 B (the size of `input_buf`). Helpers that
take a position and read via `load8(S + pos + i)` are
correct for `pos < 524288` but read STALE heap bytes for
`pos >= 524288`.

The bug surfaces as: a `#define` / `#ifdef` / `#if` /
`#derive` directive at offset > 524288 in PP_IFDEF_PASS's
processing gets a wrong hash (PP_HASH reads garbage), so
the directive is misprocessed silently — a name doesn't
get registered, an ifdef block emits when it shouldn't, etc.

v5.6.30 fixed this for `PP_DERIVE_*` (struct-deriving
helpers: serialize, deser, accessors) by threading
`src_base` through the helpers + `PP_PARSE_STRUCT_DEF`.
v5.6.42 closed the rest of the family — `PP_HASH`,
`PP_DEFINE`, `PP_DEFINED`, `PP_GETVAL`, `PP_EVAL_IF` —
which were still using `S + pos` for source reads.

FIX SHAPE:

    # Before:
    fn PP_HASH(S, pos) { ... load8(S + pos + i) ... }
    fn PP_DEFINE(S, pos) { ... }
    # ... etc

    # After:
    fn PP_HASH(src_base, pos) { ... load8(src_base + pos + i) ... }
    fn PP_DEFINE(S, src_base, pos) { ... }   # S kept for flag-table writes at S+0x90800
    # ... etc

CALLERS:
- `PP_PASS` reads from raw input at S+0 → passes `S` as src_base.
- `PP_IFDEF_PASS` reads from the `tmp` mmap buffer → passes `tmp` as src_base.

DETECTION: grep `lex_pp.cyr` for any helper that takes a
`pos` parameter and reads via `load8(S + pos + ...)` or
`load8(S + pos)`. If that helper is called from
`PP_IFDEF_PASS` with a `pos` derived from walking the `tmp`
buffer, it has the same bug.

WHY THE BUG IS LATENT FOR MOST TEST FIXTURES: top-level
`#define` / `#ifdef` / `#if` directives in the source are
caught by `PP_PASS` on the first pass, so they never reach
`PP_IFDEF_PASS`. The bug only triggers when a directive
appears INSIDE included content that PP_PASS doesn't
process (typically nested-include cases that need a 2nd
pass) AND the directive lands past offset 524288 in the
expanded output.

REGRESSION GATE: `tests/tcyr/preprocessor_past_cap.tcyr`
(v5.6.42) exercises the helpers under > 524288 B
expansion. The fix is defensive — even when the test
doesn't trip the latent path, the code shape is now
correct by inspection.

[[entries]]
name = "heap_cap_growth_pattern_compiler_grows_to_fit_language"
description = "v5.6.40 + v5.6.43 — when a stdlib bump or test fixture pushes a compiler cap (preprocessor buffer / output_buf / fixup table / fn count), the right answer is to grow the cap, not trim the stdlib / test / language. Reshuffle methodology: top-down sed substitution + disambiguation discipline for new-addr-equals-old-addr collision points."
category = "cyrius"
---
LESSON: when a dep bump (patra 1.6.0 → 1.8.3 at v5.6.40,
sigil 2.9.0 → 2.9.3 at v5.6.43) or a test fixture pushes a
compiler-internal cap, the correct response is to grow the
cap. Suggesting that the user trim a stdlib include or test
fixture to fit the existing cap is telling them to
minimize their language because the compiler can't keep up
— that's the wrong direction.

Caps that hit during v5.6.x:
- v5.6.40: preprocess_out 1 MB → 2 MB (patra 1.8.3 +
  full stdlib include set crossed 1 MB by ~280 B on
  large_input.tcyr).
- v5.6.43: output_buf 1 MB → 2 MB (sigil 2.9.3's bigger
  code put `large_input.tcyr` ELF output at ~1.08 MB —
  past the 1 MB cap).

RESHUFFLE METHODOLOGY (proven in v5.6.40, repeated cleanly
in v5.6.43):

1. **Bump the buffer size** at its base offset (e.g.,
   `preprocess_out [1048576]` → `[2097152]`).
2. **Shift every region after** by the delta. Apply
   substitutions TOP-DOWN (highest old offset first)
   to avoid sed collisions.
3. **Update cap-check sites** in `EB` / `EMITELF_*`
   (1048576 → 2097152 in the `if (filesz > ...)` and
   diagnostic strings).
4. **Update the brk syscall arg** in every main_*.cyr.
5. **Update heap-map docs** in main.cyr (authoritative)
   and the 4 main_*.cyr siblings. Watch for stale
   "21.5 MB" / "22.5 MB" total-heap mentions.

DISAMBIGUATION DISCIPLINE — the real cost of the reshuffle:

When NEW(region_A) = OLD(region_B), a global sed can't
tell them apart. v5.6.40 caught five collision points:

1. `var O = S + 0x64A000` was OLD output_buf base; NEW
   codebuf is also 0x64A000. Disambiguation: syntactic
   shape — `var O = S + 0x...;` always means output_buf
   base, while `S + 0x64A000 + cp/coff` means codebuf.
2. `var pfx = S + 0x64A000 + 131072` was OLD output_buf
   tail used as scratch. Comment was the ONLY clue.
3. `0x150B000` was OLD fixup_tbl (16-byte stride),
   NEW ir_cp (4-byte stride). Disambiguation: stride
   in the access pattern.
4. `0x13CA000` was OLD ir_state, NEW ir_blocks.
   Disambiguation: ir_state accessors are bare or
   `+8/+10/+18/+20`; ir_blocks accesses are `+ bi * 32`.
5. `0xECA000` was OLD ir_nodes, NEW struct_fnames.
   Disambiguation: per-file usage — ir.cyr uses 0xECA000
   as ir_nodes; parse_types.cyr uses it as struct_fnames.
   `replace_all` per-file was safe.

ACCEPTANCE CHECK after a reshuffle:

- 3-step self-host fixpoint (`cc5_a → cc5_b → cc5_c → cc5_d`
  byte-identical). Heap shifts are 32-bit immediates →
  byte counts shouldn't change unless the substitution
  chain corrupted something.
- `tests/tcyr/fncall_ceiling.tcyr` AND
  `tests/tcyr/sysv_odd_stack_args.tcyr` (post-v5.6.41) —
  these exercise calling-convention paths that cc5 itself
  doesn't trip. If a reshuffle subtly broke a code path,
  these gates surface it where self-host wouldn't.
- `tests/tcyr/large_input.tcyr` + `large_source.tcyr` +
  `preprocessor_past_cap.tcyr` — the "include everything"
  fixtures that exercise the new cap end-to-end.

WHY 1 MB → 2 MB AND NOT 4 MB: doubling each cap raise is
the right increment because the next pressure point is
typically 6–18 months out (current dep growth rates).
Going to 4 MB pre-emptively wastes ~15 MB of heap budget
when no consumer needs it. v5.6.40's 1→2 cap raise lasted
3 patches before sigil 2.9.3 needed the next one; v5.6.43's
output_buf raise will likely last longer (output sizes
grow slower than preprocess sizes since codebuf is also
1 MB capped).
